title: THE LOVE WITCH
description:
“Shot and designed with admirably compulsive attention to tone and composition, The Love Witch is a hothouse filled with deadly and seductive blooms.” - A.O. Scott, The NY Times

“Different from any other movies you'll see in this or any other year.” - Molly Laich, Vanguard Seattle

Presented on 35mm!The Love Witch is a breath of fresh air and a fruit ripe with symbolism for discussing gender politics! The film stars Samantha Robinson as Elaine, a witch who moves to a new town and begins to use spells to enrapture men in her path. She fantasizes about finding a perfect love, but as the body count begins to rise from the aftermath of her supernatural handiwork, she finds her haunted libido is surrounded by a town full of people ready for battle. Meticulously crafted on 35mm film by genre revisionist Anna Biller, this is a bubbling potent potion made of equal parts melodrama, pulp and exploitation with a heavy dose of ‘70s Technicolor. This loving homage stands apart as a contemporary genre must-see that challenges gender expectations. Smart and unmissable!

title: Brooklyn OSHA 10 Construction - Weekdays - $115
description:
Brooklyn OSHA 10 Weekday
OSHA 10-hour Construction Class



Earn you OSHA 10 card for the bargain price of only $115. You cannot work on a major construction site in New York City without this card. Take this engaging safety class and be qualified to work.

Schedule: Wednesday and Thursday, 9:00 AM - 3:00 PM

Price: $115 advanced online registration
$130 at the door

231 Norman Avenue, Suite 209
Brooklyn, NY 11222
(G train to Nassau Avenue)
Classes available in all 5 Boroughs.
Walk-ins Welcome  -  No Pre-Registration Required
 



New York Safety and Training, Inc.A Veteran owned business. Ask about our discount pricing for U.S. military veterans.

LIKE us on Facebook: www.Facebook.com/NYSafetyandTraining

Visit our website: www.NYSafetyandTraining.com

New York City Department of Buildings mandates that all workers at major construction sites must have had the OSHA 10-hour Construction Industry safety class within the last five years. DOB inspectors regularly visit job sites to check for OSHA cards, and any laborer without an OSHA card will be ejected from the job. Taking this course helps students to remain safety compliant and maintain their current employment or to become safety compliant as a first step towards qualifying to be hired in the construction field.

OSHA 10-Hour Construction Industry -- Designated Training TopicsThis training program is intended to provide entry level construction workers information about their rights, employer responsibilities, and how to file a complaint as well as how to identify, abate, avoid, and prevent job related hazards on a job site. The training covers a variety of construction industry safety and health hazards which a worker may encounter. Training will emphasize hazard identification, avoidance, control, and prevention, not OSHA standards. OSHA mandates that the 10 hours of training be broken into 7 hours of mandatory topics, 2 hours of elective topics, and 1 hour of optional topics as follows:

Mandatory - 7 hoursIntroduction to OSHA -- 2 hoursCovers workers' rights, employer responsibilities, and how to file a complaint. It includes helpful worker safety and health resources. It also provides samples of a weekly fatality and 3 catastrophe report, material data safety sheet, and the OSHA Log of Work-Related Injuries and Illnesses.

Fall Hazards in Construction - 1.25 hoursCovers fall protection and related fall hazards encountered on construction sites, including how to remain safe and the proper techniques to establish fall protection.

Electrical Hazards in Construction -- 1 hourCovers electrical hazards and the dangers involved with working with electrical equipment and circuitry within the construction field.

Struck By Hazards in Construction -- 1 hourCovers hazards on construction jobsites that relate to falling and flying objects including vehicular strikes. Emphasis is placed on recognizing the hazard and avoiding the hazard.

Caught-In-Between Hazards in Construction -- 1 hourIncludes hazard awareness of trench collapse, machine guarding, and entrapment situations where workers can be caught in operating machinery or pinched between opposing objects.

Personal Protective Equipment -- 1/2 hourCovers the proper, effective use of personal protective equipment (such as hearing protection, safety goggles, and gloves), including statistics of injuries related to the failure to properly use personal protective equipment.

Hazard Communication, Health Hazards, and Silica-- 1 hourCovers the proper way to label and catalogue hazardous materials and chemicals, such as cleaners, solvents, and paint, and how to avoid chronic exposure to hazardous substances including silica.

Elective - 2 hours The instructor will teach two to four of the following topics: Scaffold Hazard AwarenessThis topic covers scaffold hazards including falls, improper usage, improper erection, and the various safety systems to keep workers safe while using scaffolds.

Trench and Excavation HazardsExcavation and trenching are among the most hazardous construction operations. This topic introduces learners to the hazards of trench and excavation safety as it is encountered in the construction process.

Confined Space Hazard IntroductionIntroductory Hazard Training that refers to an area which is enclosed with limited access which makes it dangerous. Hazards in a confined space often include suffocation by un-breathable gases which may be present but not visible or submersion in liquids or free-flowing granular solids.

Ladder SafetyLadder Hazard awareness, including how to properly select, use, and maintain ladders to ensure construction site hazards are minimized.

Respiratory ProtectionThis topic covers the dangers associated with potential exposure to pathogenic airborne contaminants that can cause acute and chronic diseases among construction workers.

ErgonomicsThis topic teaches how the use of Ergonomics, which is fitting a job to a person, helps lessen muscle fatigue, increase productivity, and reduce the number and severity of work-related musculoskeletal disorders.

Safety and Health ProgramThis topic teaches considerations for creating, implementing, and enforcing your own workplace Safety and Health Programs.

Optional - 1 hour There is also an hour reserved for optional safety training. We can tailor an additional topic to a specific client (such as water safety if the client is a school with a swimming pool), or what most often happens is this hour is reserved for any of the previous topics that the students are particularly engaged in and want to spend more than the allotted time on. It is often helpful for the instructor to have this hour at his or her disposal to be able to devote to any topic in which the students are especially engaged.

title: Fire In the Hole - March 2, 2017 - 7pm
description:
In 1920, its coal tipple standing where once there were trees, the Blue Star Mining Company owns the valley. If coal is king, the people of the town are peasants, working like slaves in dangerous mines, paid in script, indebted to the Blue Star for life. Mary Ann Rowen, married to Tommy Jackson, has buried four sons and does not want to see her only remaining boy go into the mines. A stranger, Abe Steinman, tries to organize the miners into a union, but is betrayed by Mary Ann's husband during the strike. Spurning her husband, Mary Ann takes her son Joshua and leads the miners to victory.

PURA VIDA

WELCOME TO JUNGLE JAM 2017

Pura Vida is the Costa Rican way of life. It means “Pure Life” and it indicates a desire to live a life full of… well, Life! Jungle Jam seeks to embody the Costa Rican ethos of Pure Life by providing you with an experience that is full. This is not your typical music festival. Alongside the music, we provide the experience of worldwide travel, tropical excursions, relaxing beaches – even a monkey or two, if that’s what you want. We encourage you to take in all that Costa Rica has to offer and make for yourself a life full of life, while experiencing a truly intimate and unique musical experience.

title: Bear Grylls Outdoor Festival: North West
description:
BG Festival

Bear Grylls and his Survival team invites you to the ultimate day out for outdoor enthusiasts, fitness fanatics and adventurous families. Don’t miss out on the most action-packed day of Survival fitness adventure ever, for you, your friends and your family! There is something for everyone here – from little explorers to adult adventurers, all ages will have a blast!Our mission is simple: to encourage more families to get outdoors and embrace adventure! The best parts of life are found when you get outside your comfort zone – challenge yourself and live life boldly, Bear Grylls style! Remember our values: storms harden us and together we are stronger. Come and join us, run the courses, endure those storms and develop that tenacity and physicality to tackle life’s challenges.

Festival tickets are required for attendees aged 4+

BG Kids Race

The BG Kids Race obstacles are designed to challenge and empower children, but are not all compulsory to complete, we encourage all children to try before moving on with their race! Inspire your child to discover the wonder of nature and active learning with a trek through the BG Kids Race. The course consists of natural and purpose-built obstacles, with approximate distances of:


	A 800m - 1km course for 4-7 y/o
	A 1.5 - 2km course for 8-10 y/o
	A 2.5 - 3km course for 11-13 y/o

Our BG Kids Race heats start at 09:30 and run every half an hour until 15.00, with a break between 12:00-13:00. When registering, you will be able to choose the wave of your choice for your child.



4 - 5 Years Old - 09:30 and 13:00

6 -7 Years Old - 10:00 and 13:30

8 -10 Years Old - 10:30 and 14:00

11- 12 Years Old - 11:00 and 14:30

13 Years Old - 11:30 and 15:00



*All adults require a Festival or BGSR Adult Race (5k or 10k) ticket to gain entry to BG Kids Race. Adults should not purchase BG Kids tickets for themselves, but can run with race participants with Festival/BGSR Adult Race tickets. Participation in the race is not required but you are free to run alongside outside the race lanes if desired!

title: Social Potluck: Pasta From Scratch with Bakeologie
description:
We believe in preparing and eating food together with family―and that means YOU. Our social potlucks are your opportunity to keep cooking time social, share your favorite recipes and give back to the community. In this space you’ll learn how to upgrade all of your pasta dishes by making pasta from scratch! All we ask is that you bring your favorite pasta sauce to share (and if it’s in a jar, we won’t judge). Come hungry, have fun, leave happy and be apart of our family.

*Please note that this is a semi-hands on class.


WHAT TO EXPECT:


	Classes are 2 to 2 1/2 hours, unless otherwise noted.
	Hands-on classes have a maximum capacity of 16 students. -
	Meals are prepared and enjoyed at one large family style table so please be -prepared to work and eat in groups.
	You will be standing, cooking and working for most of the class. Please wear comfortable close-toed shoes. Aprons are provided to protect your clothes. -
	You will enjoy a generous taste of every dish.

ALLERGY/DIETARY RESTRICTIONS: Please specify any dietary restrictions in the designated area during checkout. This will allow us to appropriately accommodate your needs prior to class.

LOCATION: 1719 Elm Street, Cincinnati OH 45202

PARKING: Street parking is available in front of the Findlay Kitchen building. Additional parking can be found in any of the surrounding Findlay Market lots. (http://www.findlaymarket.org/parking)

REFUND POLICY: Due to limited seating and the upfront costs of food and preparation, our cooking classes and events are non-refundable. If you are unable to attend, we encourage you to transfer your seat to someone else; however, all sales are final and cannot be refunded.

title: Gridiron Glory - "The Best of Pro Football HOF"
description:
Texas Southern University (TSU) is proud to be selected as                         Houston’s host institution for Gridiron Glory: The Best of the Pro Football                         Hall of Fame. This 6,000 square-foot exhibit will be housed in TSU’s                         University Museum beginning January 30, 2017.                         This one-of-a-kind interactive multimedia experience includes clips from NFL                         Films, specialized fan experiences, and a “Hometown Tribute” section to                         spotlight the Houston Texans and TSU’s Tigers in the NFL. Attendees can also                         enjoy the exhibit’s educational programming as well as visits from Pro Football Hall of                         Famers.

The Gridiron                         Glory exhibit will be supplemented with the new Black College Football                         Hall of Fame display and Tigers in the NFL, a tribute to TSU players                         who made their mark in the League. This will position the Gridiron Glory                         Exhibition at Texas Southern University as a destination for football fans                         unlike any other locations on the exhibit’s tour.

There                         are several ways to become involved with this exciting initiative, which will                         raise money for student scholarships and support programs at TSU. They are:                         sponsorships and partnerships, venue rental, memorabilia, souvenir booklet ads                         and museum tickets. Only 500 tickets per day will be available to visit the                         exhibit. For additional information, visit the website at www.tsu.edu
                                                  The                         exhibit will reside on the TSU campus for three months beginning January 30,                         2017 through April 30, 2017—before, during, and months after Super Bowl LI                         which will be played in Houston at NRG Stadium on February 5, 2017.

title: AGO - Women and Art tour
description:
Join us on Tuesday February 21st, 2017 at 11am for a "Women in Art" tour at the AGO - Art Gallery of Ontario.

Discover how women artists have been involved in making art throughout history by exploring the AGO's collections, including European, Canadian, African, Photography and Contemporary. Join us on a journey through the indelible influence of women in art.

The tour will last about 1 hour. Babies and walking children are welcomed. The tour can accommodate strollers or baby carriers.

The fee for the event is $24 for AGO members and $36 for non-members. For non-members the fee includes admission to the museum and the group private tour. You can stay and browse the museum at your leisure following the tour.

50% of each ticket sold will go towards the Art Strollers fund, at the end of 2016 the cumulation of the fund will be allocated to art organizations in Toronto offering family programming.



About Art Strollers

Our purpose is to bridge families and art organizations, art institutions, galleries and artists. By engaging families with the arts, we strive to enrich not only the lives of the children and parents but also to contribute to the art world's reach and growth for current and future generations. It is a dual purpose to engage the future generations in appreciating and sustaining the continuous creation and presentation of art - visual and performing.

www.artstrollers.ca

title: Keep Austin Agile 2017
description:
On May 25, 2017, join the Austin community at the fifth Agile Austin conference, Keep Austin Agile 2017. Our fourth conference, Keep Austin Agile 2016, sold out with over 725 attendees. The 2017 conference will provide opportunities for current agile professionals and beginners alike to go beyond practices by understanding the principles behind agile and how to apply them within your organization.

This one day event will offer various tracks for education and networking in a relaxed environment at the JW Marriott in Austin, Texas. Whether a project manager, scrum master, developer, tester, operations team member, product manager, or executive, this conference is for everyone currently involved with agile projects or just investigating its merits.

Cancellation Policy: 
	

Because the Keep Austin Agile conference incurs expenses prior to the conference, it is necessary to impose the following cancellation policy:

Cancellations received by May 4, 2017 will be issued a full refund less processing and handling fees.

No refund of any kind, for any reason (including medical emergencies) will be given for cancellation requests received after May 4, 2017.

Swaps from the same organization are welcome at no additional fee. If you need to swap with another attendee, please do so through the ticketing application.

No-shows are liable for the entire conference fee. Please send any questions to registration@agileaustin.org.

Hotel Room Information:

Agile Austin has arranged a discounted room rate of $229 a night (plus tax) for attendees of Keep Austin Agile 2017 at the JW Marriott. The special rate is in effect until May 5, 2017 or until rooms are sold out. Click here to reserve your room today!

Parking is not included in the hotel room rate or conference fee.

Where to Park for the Conference:
	

We highly encourage carpooling to the event and/or using public transportation.

Below are alternative parking garages that might be appropriate:

Austin Convention Center 2nd Street Garage: 201 East 2nd Street, Austin, TX 78701. Entrances are on Brazos and San Jacinto street.

Austin Convention Center 5th Street Garage: 601 E. 5th Street, Austin, TX 78701. Entrance is on 5th Street.

Current pricing for both parking garages are:

7 – 9 hours: $9

9 – 12 hours: $15

12 hours +: $30

Your Information:
	

We share the contact and agile-related information you provide when you register with some of the official sponsors of Keep Austin Agile 2017. The funding we receive from our sponsors helps make this conference possible and affordable. Sponsors may use this information to promote their agile-related products and services to you, but may not share it with others or use it for any other purpose without your permission.  Sponsors will remove you from their contact lists at your request.

title: Easy Weeknight Indian with Tablespoon Cooking Co.
description:
Imagine vibrant colors, aromas, heat and richness all coming together in your kitchen… on a weeknight… after a long day at work! No, we aren’t talking about getting take out from the local curry house! 

Chef Catrina’s easy and flavorful menu will include chicken tikka masala, fragrant jasmine rice, grilled naan and mango lassis. 

We’ll talk about how to have a plan in place, prep your ingredients in advance, and easily pull off this delicious dinner without breaking a sweat! You’ll make your own garam masala, then learn how to use it to flavor your main dish while perfectly steaming your rice and adding a little flavor to your naan. In this class, you’ll be exposed to new ingredients and cooking techniques, learn how to incorporate a new cuisine into your weeknight cooking, and have fun while making new friends! 


About Chef Catrina Mills

Chef Catrina Mills specializes in international cuisine. After growing up in Chicago and New Orleans,  she traveled the world while serving in the Air Force. Chef Catrina received her culinary training from Midwest Culinary Institute and the University of Cincinnati. In addition to her work as a culinary instructor, culinologist and published author,  she owns a catering business and also sells her own line of spices.


Important Event Details

CLASS FORMAT: This is a hands-on class. Everyone will have a station with tools and equipment. We will all work together to cook the recipes. Everyone will get their hands dirty and be involved in the recipes. Some recipes will be mostly demonstrations and others will be completely hands-on. This class is limited to 12 students.

FOOD: Class will end with everyone eating dinner together. After we’re done cooking, we will sit down to enjoy everything we made! You won’t leave hungry.

ALLERGIES AND DIETARY RESTRICTIONS: Please let us know of any allergies or dietary restrictions IN ADVANCE and we can talk about accommodations.

DRINKS: We provide local craft beer, wine, and bottled water. You are welcome to bring any non-alcoholic drinks to class with you.

ADDRESS: Findlay Kitchen is located at 1719 Elm St. Cincinnati, OH 45202

PARKING: There is often street parking available or you can park in one of the Findlay Market lots. Parking info can be found on the Findlay Market website. It will only cost a few dollars.

ARRIVAL: The classroom kitchen is all windows and located directly inside the front doors. You’ll see us when you walk up. The doors will be locked so just knock and we’ll let you in. We will be watching for arrivals so it shouldn’t be an issue. Please try to arrive by 5:45 pm so we can get started on time.

ATTIRE: Please wear closed toed shoes such as sneakers. You want your feet to be covered (we'll be working with knives and hot soup!) and you want to wear something comfortable since we will be on our feet for a few hours. Please keep your hair pulled back or wear a hat. Otherwise, wear comfortable clothes that could potentially get a little dirty. We will provide aprons. Also, feel free to bring clothes if you need to change after work. There is a nice, clean bathroom where you can change.

WHAT TO BRING: Nothing!

Questions? Email jordan@tablespooncookingco.com

title: 2017 Freedom Festival (17-19 March)
description:
Held every year in March, The Freedom Festival is an amazing weekend for anyone who cares about freedom and liberty. You will be able to play an active part in discussions and debates about the big political, economic and moral issues of the day. Over the weekend those who attend rub shoulders with some of the most inspirational pro-freedom speakers from across the UK and overseas, including writers, politicians, academics, journalists, economists and philosophers.

We're expanding the Festival for 2017, so, while the main events will continue to be held at the Marsham Court Hotel, for those of you who would like a change of scenery, you will now also be able to stay at the Hotel Miramar, just a 3-minute walk away, for a small additional charge. Only 10 rooms are available at The Miramar - when they're gone, they're gone!

The Miramar will also be the setting for a drinks reception, two-course dinner and coffee on the Friday evening - all included in the price of the Festival. You'll enjoy the elegant, traditional style of The Miramar. J.R.R. Tolkien - author of Lord of the Rings and The Hobbit - holidayed there regularly from the 1950s to the 1970s, so Dr. Ted Bromund, Senior Research Fellow at The Heritage Foundation, and a Freedom Festival stalwart, will give us a talk on 'Tolkien and Conservatism' - a subject on which he is an expert authority.

Single rooms are available at both hotels for a supplement of £40 per weekend, and rooms with a sea view are available at the Marsham Court Hotel only for a supplement of £30 per weekend. Sea view rooms are popular, so book early to avoid disappointment. 

For those of you arriving on Friday afternoon, we have arranged afternoon tea and a guided tour of the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum (opposite the Marsham Court Hotel) for a special price of just £25, which includes the price of admission.

Organised by The Freedom Association, it is always a weekend to remember.

FULL PRICE LIST

£259.00 – Full Weekend All-Inclusive Ticket. Accommodation at the Marsham Court Hotel. Price per person, based on two people sharing a double or twin room.

Includes the reception, dinner and speakers at The Miramar on Friday evening, two nights’ en suite accommodation including full English breakfast at the Marsham Court Hotel, all of the debates, discussions etc., tea and coffee breaks, lunch and dinner on Saturday, together with coffee and further sessions on Sunday.

£289.00 – Full Weekend All-Inclusive Ticket. Accommodation at the Hotel Miramar. Price per person, based on two people sharing a double or twin room.includes the reception, dinner and speakers at The Miramar, two nights’ en suite accommodation including full English breakfast at The Miramar, all of the debates, discussions etc., tea and coffee breaks, lunch and dinner on Saturday, together with coffee and further sessions on Sunday.

£40.00 – Single Room Supplement per room for two nights (both Marsham Court Hotel & Hotel Miramar)

£30.00 – Sea view supplement per room for two nights. (Marsham Court Hotel only)

£25.00 – Afternoon Tea, guided tour of the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum, including admission fee (Friday afternoon)

£89.00 - Student Ticket: For a special price, students get full board accommodation for two nights in Bournemouth. Included in the price is the reception, dinner and speakers at The Miramar on Friday evening, all of the debates, discussions etc., tea and coffee breaks, lunch and dinner on Saturday, together with coffee and further sessions on Sunday.

Please note: this offer is only available to full-time university students aged 18-25 years. Students must be prepared to share a twin room. ROAR

title: Bear Grylls Outdoor Festival: London
description:
BG Festival

Bear Grylls and his Survival team invites you to the ultimate day out for outdoor enthusiasts, fitness fanatics and adventurous families. Don’t miss out on the most action-packed day of Survival fitness adventure ever, for you, your friends and your family! There is something for everyone here – from little explorers to adult adventurers, all ages will have a blast!Our mission is simple: to encourage more families to get outdoors and embrace adventure! The best parts of life are found when you get outside your comfort zone – challenge yourself and live life boldly, Bear Grylls style! Remember our values: storms harden us and together we are stronger. Come and join us, run the courses, endure those storms and develop that tenacity and physicality to tackle life’s challenges.

A Festival Ticket is required for all attendees aged 4+BG Kids Race

The BG Kids Race obstacles are designed to challenge and empower children, but are not all compulsory to complete, we encourage all children to try before moving on with their race! Inspire your child to discover the wonder of nature and active learning with a trek through the BG Kids Race. The course consists of natural and purpose-built obstacles, with approximate distances of:


	A 800m - 1km course for 4-7 y/o
	A 1.5 - 2km course for 8-10 y/o
	A 2.5 - 3km course for 11-13 y/o

Our BG Kids Race heats start at 09:30 and run every half an hour until 15.00, with a break between 12:00-13:00. When registering, you will be able to choose the wave of your choice for your child.

4 - 5 Years Old - 09:30 and 13:00

6 -7 Years Old - 10:00 and 13:30

8 -10 Years Old - 10:30 and 14:00

Adults should not purchase BG Kids tickets for themselves, but can run with race participants with Festival/BGSR Adult Race tickets. title: AGO - Patrons and Collectors tour
description:
Join us on Wednesday March 22nd, 2017 at 11am for a "Patrons and Collectors" tour at the AGO - Art Gallery of Ontario.

In this fascinating tour discover how the art world, through collecting and patronage, is a business. Experience our collections while considering the artistic innovations, networks and funding systems. Explore the Sarick Collection of Inuit Art; the Frum Collection of African Art; and the Thomson Collection of European and Canadian Art to learn how such impressive collections are built and sustained.

The tour will last about 1 hour. Babies and walking children are welcomed. The tour can accommodate strollers or baby carriers.

The fee for the event is $24 for AGO members and $36 for non-members. For non-members the fee includes admission to the museum and the group private tour. You can stay and browse the museum at your leisure following the tour.

50% of each ticket sold will go towards the Art Strollers fund, at the end of 2016 the cumulation of the fund will be allocated to art organizations in Toronto offering family programming.



About Art Strollers

Our purpose is to bridge families and art organizations, art institutions, galleries and artists. By engaging families with the arts, we strive to enrich not only the lives of the children and parents but also to contribute to the art world's reach and growth for current and future generations. It is a dual purpose to engage the future generations in appreciating and sustaining the continuous creation and presentation of art - visual and performing.

www.artstrollers.ca

title: Uncork Ontario — Winter Wine Tour
description:
Uncork Ontario
Winter Wine Tour
Saturday, February 25, 2017
Join us for the ultimate winter wine tour as we explore the Niagara Escarpment, a VQA sub-appellation and one of Canada’s first UNESCO World Biosphere Reserves. Michael Fagan, a former columnist for the LCBO’s Food & Drink magazine, will be your expert tour guide as we wine and dine at some of the most renowned wineries in the Niagara.

We'll sample and discuss the prestigious sparkling and apéritif wines of Cave Spring Cellars with their Winemaker, Gabriel Demarco. He'll guide us through a tasting of their premium Estate Bottled wines, and prestigious CSV-labelled wines made in small allotments, using the finest fruit from Cave Spring Vineyard’s oldest vines.

At Redstone Winery, we'll enjoy a three-course lunch with wine pairings at their recently opened and locally-inspired restaurant. Named for its red clay soil and large stones, Redstone Winery is the latest venture by Moray Tawse.

Nearby, Tawse Winery will guide us through a curated tasting of their famed Burgundian-inspired cool climate wines. We'll sample some of the finest Chardonnays and Pinot Noirs of their portfolio. Vineland Estates Winery's sommelier will give us an in-depth lesson on Icewine production. We’ll taste their award-winning Icewines and enjoy a variety of cheese, charcuterie and desserts.

Sign up today and for a winter winery adventure in Niagara!

Itinerary:


	
	8:30 a.m: Meet at George Brown College (300 Adelaide St. East) for coffee and breakfast snacks
	
	9:00 a.m: Depart for Cave Spring Cellars
	
	10:30 a.m: Tasting at Cave Spring Cellars
	
	12:15 p.m: Enjoy a three-course lunch with wine at Redstone Winery
	
	2:00 p.m: Winery tour and tasting at Tawse Winery
	
	3:30 p.m: Winery tour and tasting at Vineland Estates Winery
	
	5:30 p.m: Depart for 300 Adelaide St E.
	
	7:00 p.m: Approximate arrival time



Details:

	Tickets are $175 per person for groups of two or more, and $200 for individual passes
	All transportation on a coach bus, leaving from      and returning to 300 Adelaide St. East
	A full day's tour and lessons, led by      our industry expert

title: Mardi Gras Favorites with Tablespoon Cooking Co.
description:
Spend Fat Tuesday cooking, eating, and indulging with us! Whether it’s rich and flavorful Creole or rustic and earthy Cajun, this Mardi Gras menu is the perfect way to experience the flavors of the Crescent City without leaving home. 

Chef Catrina Mills was raised in New Orleans and she’s ready to teach you everything she knows about Louisiana cooking. 

Learn to make your own gumbo with a perfect dark roux, eat a true jambalaya and learn exactly how to re-create it at home and master a classic New Orleans bread pudding with bourbon sauce. In the spirit of Mardi Gras, laissez les bons temps rouler! Let the good times roll!




Menu


	Gumbo with Shrimp, Crab, Chicken and Andouille Sausage
	Cajun Jambalaya
	Bread Pudding with Bourbon Glaze

About Chef Catrina Mills

Chef Catrina Mills specializes in international cuisine. After growing up in Chicago and New Orleans,  she traveled the world while serving in the Air Force. Chef Catrina received her culinary training from Midwest Culinary Institute and the University of Cincinnati. In addition to her work as a culinary instructor, culinologist and published author,  she owns a catering business and also sells her own line of spices.


Important Event Details

CLASS FORMAT: This is a hands-on class. Everyone will have a station with tools and equipment. We will all work together to cook the recipes. Everyone will get their hands dirty and be involved in the recipes. Some recipes will be mostly demonstrations and others will be completely hands-on. This class is limited to 12 students.

FOOD: Class will end with everyone eating dinner together. After we’re done cooking, we will sit down to enjoy everything we made! You won’t leave hungry.

ALLERGIES AND DIETARY RESTRICTIONS: Please let us know of any allergies or dietary restrictions IN ADVANCE and we can talk about accommodations.

DRINKS: We provide local craft beer, wine, and bottled water. You are welcome to bring any non-alcoholic drinks to class with you.

ADDRESS: Findlay Kitchen is located at 1719 Elm St. Cincinnati, OH 45202

PARKING: There is often street parking available or you can park in one of the Findlay Market lots. Parking info can be found on the Findlay Market website. It will only cost a few dollars.

ARRIVAL: The classroom kitchen is all windows and located directly inside the front doors. You’ll see us when you walk up. The doors will be locked so just knock and we’ll let you in. We will be watching for arrivals so it shouldn’t be an issue. Please try to arrive by 5:45 pm so we can get started on time.

ATTIRE: Please wear closed toed shoes such as sneakers. You want your feet to be covered (we'll be working with knives and hot food!) and you want to wear something comfortable since we will be on our feet for a few hours. Please keep your hair pulled back or wear a hat. Otherwise, wear comfortable clothes that could potentially get a little dirty. We will provide aprons. Also, feel free to bring clothes if you need to change after work. There is a nice, clean bathroom where you can change.

WHAT TO BRING: Nothing!

Questions? Email jordan@tablespooncookingco.com

title: CLARITY
description:
On Friday, April 28, 2017 prepare to connect with your community in a profoundly memorable way at CLARITY, an interactive social event to benefit TranQuility. This is an innovative approach to not only educating and empowering people, but also fostering closeness in your community in the most memorable way.

CLARITY is a one hour innovative and upbeat educational program that gives people the practical, proven knowledge they need to create lasting relationships and become the people they were meant to be.

CLARITY teaches us the common roadblocks to love, and shows us how to begin shifting our paths and adjusting our sails. The more connected we are with ourselves, the better equipped we will be to foster healthy, genuine connections with others. CLARITY, the new model for love.

The event features 3 parts:  Education hour, an Empower hour and an After Party.

Discover: Clarity begins with a fun, interactive educational experience that clarifies why relationships don’t work, how to achieve a fulfilling relationship, and ways to personally grow to reach one’s full potential.

Relate: Next, in the Empower hour, participants engage with one another in an exciting activity that enables them to apply their new knowledge in a safe, inclusive environment.



Connect: The event concludes with a VIP After Party at University Club in Downtown Gainesville where attendees are invited to explore connections with like-minded individuals and enjoy food, complimentary drink, photo booth and dancing to commemorate the experience.

Alachua TranQuility is a community group for Transgender or Gender non-conforming individuals, or family/friends of such people who would like to be supportive in their loved ones' journeys. They are dedicated to educating, supporting and caring for people of all gender identities. 

facebook.com/alachua.tranquility

title: Siris Cask Festival
description:
Celebrating the Women of Craft Beer, Celebrating the Craft Beer of Women

The Tri-Cities Cask Festival Association is proud to announce The Siris Cask Festival, a Craft Cask event featuring 30+ beers brewed exclusively by women.

The goal of the festival is to provide a venue to showcase the amazing skill of our female brewers, reaching back to a time when the important duty of brewing beer was exclusively the role of women in society. Siris was the original goddess of beer in pre-Sumerian mythology.

The other goal for the festival is to provide a bursary for Kwantlen Polytechnic University’s Brewing Studies program. The bursary will be available to female students, with the intention of helping achieve gender parity in the brewing industry.

In keeping with spirit of the festival, the first hour will be open only to women. After that hour, the ticketed public will be allowed in.

Some quick answers to your questions: 

When, Where, How: April 22nd 2017, at the Cat and Fiddle Pub, 11 am to 5 pm (1st hour open only to women).

 Participating Breweries are:


	
	Moody Ales Featured Brewer Roxanne Cartwright
	
	Yellow Dog Brewing
	KPU Brewing & Brewery Operations Program Female Students
	More to be announced as they officially register, check back regularly

Who are the brewers?

 There are only three craft breweries in BC that have women designated as head brewers, but there are dozens of women working at every craft brewery. We approached almost all of BC’s craft brewers to have their female staff produce casks for Siris. The response was immediate and enthusiastic.

Breweries that didn’t have a woman as an active member of their fermentation staff almost all had women working for them with brewing skills—either attending brewing school or as home brewers, or from working with other breweries in the past—who stepped in and brewed, again with enthusiasm.

For breweries without the benefit of female brewers in-house, we were able to connect them with female brewers from inside the industry: cicerones, inside staff, account managers, and others who had the skill and love of brewing. In the end, it all came together.

For an updated list of all the breweries and a short bio of each brewer, please click on this link SIRIS BREWERS BIO'S

Special Event Sponsors:



FAQs

What do I get with my ticket?

Each ticket includes access to the event, 10oz Tasting Glass, 10 tokens for 4oz tasting (you can use 2 tokens to have the glass filled), Event Program, Entry in to the Door Prize Draws. If you choose the T-Shirt option it will include one Siris Cask Festival T-Shirt in the size you indicate.   Additional tokens will be available at the venue for $2 each.

 

What do I need to get in?

You will need to present your ticket in either paper form or on your digital device. 2 pieces of valid ID

Females only for the first hour?

In celebrating the women of craft brewing we want to also recognize the female consumers of craft beer with giving them the first hour 11am-Noon with out the male consumers. Event will open to everyone at Noon.

Are you women? Who’s running the show?

No, we’re a non-profit society that organizes the largest and best-attended cask festivals in BC. We’ve done the behind-the-scenes organizing to get the space and the casks together, but it’s not our show—we are just holding the curtain for the important players, the brewers.

So are you speaking for the women of brewing?

 No. The Women of Craft Brewing don’t need anybody to speak for them. All they need is a place to speak for themselves. As such the TCCFA has only two mandates: to facilitate a great cask festival, and to use ticket proceeds to endow a bursary available to female students at KPU. The rest of the festival is up to the brewers themselves. We’re as excited as anyone to see where they take it. That’s part of the reason why it’s women-only in the first hour: networking, celebrating, sharing and enjoying great beer.

 How much is the bursary? How will it be awarded?
	

 Our pledge to KPU is set at $1500 for this festival. We’re planning on driving that number higher—as high as we can—through merchandise sales and donations. The award criteria is handled by the finance department at KPU, but the award will go to a female student entering their second year who demonstrates financial need and meets the minimum GPA.

 Is that a depiction of Siris in your logo? Isn’t Ninkasi the goddess of brewers?
	

 It’s actually a stylized image of Innana, the mother-goddess that originated in Uruk. There are no definitively identifiable images of Siris, or indeed of Ninkasi. Siris actually preceded Ninkasi as the goddess of beer and brewing among the Semite peoples and later got folded into Sumerian mythology as a daemon daughter of Ninkasi. We chose Siris because she was earliest, and because there’s a famous brewery named after Ninkasi that we didn’t want to be confused with. Ancient anthropology is fun, but not simple.
Is the registration/ticket transferable?
Yes. Tickets can be gifted. As long as the ticket can be presented either in paper or digitally everything is fine.
Can I get Tickets at the door?
If the event is not sold out tickets will be available at the door for $45.

Are there ID requirements or an age limit to enter the event?

This
 is a 19 + event. No admittance under the age of 19. We will be 
requiring 2 pieces of valid ID to enter the venue. If you do not have ID
 you will be turned away and no refund will be provided.
What are my transport/parking options getting to the event?
There
 will be plenty of parking on site and surrounding area. Taxi service is 
available, public transit is just step from the venue and there are 
several services that can drive you and your vehicle home.

What is the refund policy?

The
 registration deadline is January 22nd, 2017. Full refunds are 
available prior to January 14th, 2017. There will be no ticket sales 
and no refunds at the event. After this date no refunds will be offered.
 To request a cancellation or to make a change please send an email to 
info@tricitiescaskfestival.com

If you have any other questions, please send us a note to info@sirisfestival.com and put ‘Siris’ in the subject line. We’ll get back to you with an answer.

Are you with media and would like to contact us? Please email media@sirisfestival.com

title: From script to screen: An evening with award-winning screenwriter and debut
description:
Waterstones Manchester Deansgate and Manchester Film Festival are 
delighted to host an evening with Canadian debut author and 
award-winning screenwriter Elan Mastai. Elan has written five feature 
films and produced two, most recently
 'What If' starring Daniel Radcliffe, Adam Driver, Zoe Kazan, Mackenzie 
Davis, and Rafe Spall. 'What If' premiered at the Toronto International 
Film Festival and won both the Canadian Academy Award and the Writers 
Guild of Canada Award for the script. As a
 screenwriter, Elan has a  written movies for many of the Hollywood 
studios, including Paramount, Warner Brothers, Fox, and Sony. Elan will 
be talking about writing for screen, and about his very cinematic debut 
novel "All Our Wrong Todays"; part literary fiction,
 part science-fiction, Elan's debut novel is at once a love story, a 
mainstream time travel adventure and a coming-of-age novel. His novel 
has already being translated into two dozen languages. The film rights 
have been sold to Paramount Pictures, with Amy
 Pascal producing, and Elan is currently writing the screenplay 
adaptation of his novel for the big screen.

title: Bata Shoe Museum - Highlights tour
description:
Join us on Thursday April 6th, 2016 at 11am for a guided tour of the Bata Shoe Museum.

Lead by a Bata Shoe Museum docent, this tour will highlight the Bata Show Museum's four impressive galleries. Footwear on display ranges from Chinese bound foot shoes and ancient Egyptian sandals to chestnut-crushing clogs and glamorous platforms. Over 4,500 years of history and a collection of 20th-century celebrity shoes are reflected in the semi-permanent exhibition, All About Shoes. Three other galleries featuring their current exhibits - "Standing Tall", "Fashion VIctims" and "Art & Innovation"

The tour will last about 1 hour. Babies and walking children are welcomed. We strongly recommend baby carriers for this tour.  There will be a designated area to leave the strollers during the duration of the tour.

The fee for the event is $22 and includes admission to the museum and the group private tour. You can stay and browse the museum at your leisure following the tour.

50% of each ticket sold will go towards the Art Strollers fund, at the end of 2016 the cumulation of the fund will be allocated to art organizations in Toronto offering family programming.



About Art Strollers

Our purpose is to bridge families and art organizations, art institutions, galleries and artists. By engaging families with the arts, we strive to enrich not only the lives of the children and parents but also to contribute to the art world's reach and growth for current and future generations. It is a dual purpose to engage the future generations in appreciating and sustaining the continuous creation and presentation of art - visual and performing.

www.artstrollers.ca

title: Ladies of Burlesque: McCABE & MRS. MILLER
description:
LADIES of BURLESQUE pays tribute to the legendary Leonard Cohen with McCABE & MRS. MILLER—Robert Altman’s iconic, critically acclaimed anti-Western. Featuring the most beautiful and haunting music Cohen ever composed, McCABE & MRS. MILLER revels in the “Maestro of Melancholy’s” ability to capture the essence of doomed romance and the elusive, bewitching women that only Cohen could conjure. With Sam Antics on stage performing a seductive Cohen-dedicated burlesque, this is a LADIES of BURLESQUE that plays it close to the heart.

Warren Beatty is John McCabe, a gambler who establishes a low-rent brothel in a rough-and-tumble Old West mining town. Ill-equipped to deal with the particulars of this new business and unable to inspire the prostitutes (one of which is played by Shelley Duvall) to greater professional heights, McCabe is easily swayed into partnering with the newly-arrived Constance Miller (Julie Christie)—an experienced Madam and keen business woman. Together, they turn the brothel around and business flourishes. When mining company agents threaten McCabe and Mrs. Miller after they refuse to sell their land, McCabe is forced to fight for his community of gamblers and prostitutes, precipitating a shoot out sequence that defies all Westerns that came before.

Altman found divine inspiration in Cohen’s debut album, “Songs of Leonard Cohen” when writing the film and the director fought hard to secure rights to it. Cohen’s lyrics—with visuals of deathly winter, cold-hearted women, and men desperate for comfort—define the film’s iconography and mood, leading to one of the most significant uses of music in film, and a masterpiece (both musical and visual) like no other.

It’s a bluegrass inspired night of music and joy... beards, banjos, and blessings for the whole family! A night of corporate worship; with hymns, choruses, original songs, and comedy, geared towards all ages and denominations. It’s Baptists, Pentecostals, Catholics (and everything in between). It’s the local churches coming together to worship in unity, It’s a HOOTENANNY!

title: The Third Annual Swanktacular
description:
Join the Baltimore Rock Opera Society in our epic quest to find a Forever Home in Baltimore City! At this benefit party the BROS will join forces with one of the most exciting symphonic organizations in Baltimore: Occasional Symphony. If you liked Convergence Maximus, this is an evening of revelry you don’t want to miss! The crown jewel of the evening will be a totally unique and collaborative performance from our very first rock opera, Gründlehämmer, featuring the original shadowplay! The program will also feature Occasional Symphony’s most epic pieces and additional symphonic collaborations with BROS musicians.

Our silent auction this year features tons of amazing local items, as well as two “best-in-the house” tickets to Hamilton on Broadway on your choice of dates! Yes, you read that right.

Closing out the night is Sarah Sullivan and the New Old Fashioneds, bringing you the best classics of swing and jazz. We’ll have a delicious spread of gourmet foods provided by some of your favorite local restaurants including Birroteca and Blue Pit BBQ, accompanied by an equally titillating selection of local drinks. Hosted at Baltimore’s historic 2640 Space, a perfect backdrop to spin our rags into royalty. We invite you to dress in your best medieval finery or your swankiest partygoing threads.

The Occasional Symphony is a Baltimore grassroots orchestra whose mission is to create innovative concert celebrations to engage the Baltimore community and illuminate the unparalleled experience of hearing live music curated for living spaces.

Click here to see photos from our previous Swanktacular photobooth!
Join BROS to create a rock palace that will enrich Baltimore for the next 7,000 years! For sponsorship opportunities, please visit baltimorerockopera.org/sponsor.

title: Immersive Art tour:  Artist studio: Elsha Leventis
description:
Join us on Friday March 24th, 2016 at 11am for an immersive art tour of artist Elsha Leventis' studio in the Distillery District.

Our immersive art tour series includes a private gallery tour followed by a short classical violin performance in the exhibit. We believe that we can engage with art in many forms. At the end of the art tour, violinist Ivana Popovic, will play three short solo violin pieces. Her musical selection will be based on the art theme, period, meaning and various other elements which will enhance the viewing experience. Pieces will be selected from the classical, modern repertoire or composed for the purpose of the exhibit.

During this tour, Elsha Leventis, will talk about her art, her inspiration and her journey as an artist and mother.  The talk will be followed by a short solo violin performance.

Note:  given the smaller size of the studio, it will be a very intimate tour.

The tour will take place in Elsha Leventis' studio located in the Case Goods Artscape Building on the ground floor.  The Artscape building is the big brown 6 floor building behind Balzac's cafe on Case Good's lane - http://www.livingatthedistillery.com/the-neighbour...

The fee for the event is $10. The tour and performance will last about 40 minutes.

50% of each ticket sold will go towards the Art Strollers fund, at the end of 2017  the cumulation of the fund will be allocated to art organizations in Toronto offering family programming.



About Art Strollers

Our purpose is to bridge families and art organizations, art institutions, galleries and artists. By engaging families with the arts, we strive to enrich not only the lives of the children and parents but also to contribute to the art world's reach and growth for current and future generations. It is a dual purpose to engage the future generations in appreciating and sustaining the continuous creation and presentation of art - visual and performing.

title: Wedding & Event Design | ONLINE
description: DescriptionProducing an aesthetically pleasing event that truly impresses seen-it-all attendees can be a daunting task. Adding to the pressure, today’s event designers are expected to incorporate food and beverage, technology, and branding and find innovative ways to play with color, create unique focal points, use lighting to make a space feel more intimate, and select florals that don’t max out the budget. Do you have the creative edge? Or, at a minimum, can you intelligently “talk the talk” with creative vendors in order to convey your vision?This course you will cover the key principles of modern event design including how to create a design concept that achieves the client's goals, meets their budget, and can be executed in the venue with the time allotted. Implement a wide range of elements into your next design concept, such as floral, furniture, lighting, branded accents, entertainment, technology and others. Identify opportunities for creating custom fabrication pieces that can be unique focal points for guests, which helps to set yourself apart from others.  By the end of the course you will be able to evaluate a venue's challenges and assets that will be incorporated into a design concept, and how to insure you can execute your vision within the time and space available.

title: Assistant Ropes Course Instructor / Level 1 (April 3)
description:
Course Description

This 40 hour entry level certification teaches the technical, facilitation, and safety management skills required to lead low and high ropes programs. Course candidates explore adventure-based facilitation, standards, and effective operating procedures as they develop the safe attitude, skills, and knowledge that enable them to work on a ropes course.

Course ObjectivesBy the end of this course, instructor candidates will:


	Have the skills to assist in high ropes operation including belaying, knot tying, set-up/take down, personal fall protection, and equipment use and care
	Be familiar with adventure learning theories and practices especially their application to program leadership
	Learn and practice safe operation and management aspects of high and low elements Experience facilitating a low activity including its design, delivery, and debrief
	Improve their ability to provide meaningful involvement opportunities for all participants

Course Prerequisites


	18 years of age
	Willingness and ability to perform all tasks related to ropes course operation including spotting, belaying, climbing on belay, climbing on self belay to perform set-up / take-down
	Previous participation in ropes course or climbing activities preferred

title: 8th Annual Laugh Out Loud in Leaside
description:
Hosted by Charlene Kalia, the 8th annual "Laugh Out Loud in Leaside" is set to take place on Friday, February 24, 2017.  The evening will include a silent and live auction, comedy, and live music.
Laugh Out Loud #8 will benefit The Maddie Project. All proceeds from LOL #8 will help support child and adolescent mental health services at North York General’s Phillip’s House, home of Maddie’s Healing Garden.


http://www.nyghfoundation.ca/maddie-project







THE MADDIE PROJECT

Madeline German Coulter was the sparkle in the room that brought laughter and energy to everyone.  When depression ended her life at just 14 years old, Maddie's family channeled their grief into purpose, creating The Maddie Project (www.themaddieproject.ca).

The Maddie Project is a community effort in support of youth struggling with depression and other mental health related concerns. Driven by community collaboration and events, the project’s goals are to raise awareness by sparking conversations about youth depression and mental health concerns as well as to help provide uninhibited access to support for youth and their families.

PHILLIPS HOUSE & MADDIE’S HEALING GARDEN

North York General has prioritized the $8M redevelopment of Phillips House, a hospital-owned heritage estate, into the home-like outpatient mental health care facility that young patients need and deserve.

To complement the developments within Phillips House, the 1.2 acres of land surrounding the building will be redeveloped into Maddie’s Healing Garden, which will play an important role in patients’ care.  The beautifully landscaped garden and fresh air will offer solace and provide energy to patients as they work through their mental health treatment toward health and recovery.


DONATE NOW

FOR MORE INFORMATION ABOUT THE EVENT, PLEASE CONTACT:

Charlene Kalia, charlene@charlenekalia.com

title: Hannahstrong Fundraiser
description:
On May 23rd, 2016, our niece, granddaughter and friend, Hannah Carroll (age 13) was diagnosed with Osteosarcoma, a form of bone cancer located in her knee. Since this devastating news, Hannah has gone through 8 rounds of excruciating chemotherapy scheduled to be as long as fifty hours per round. Prior to her diagnosis, Hannah was an ice-skater, cheerleader and volleyball player. On August 23rd  2016, Hannah underwent complete reconstructive surgery to install a new prosthetic knee. After this procedure, the tumor was removed, and her prognosis has improved tremendously. However, Hannah needs to undergo 10 more rounds of chemotherapy, which will keep her from going back to school for her eighth grade year. Instead,... she will be tutored at home and in the hospital, where she will miss out on all of her eighth grade activities. Not only will Hannah be unable to attend school, she will also be unable to participate in her extracurricular activities. Needless to say, this unfortunate situation has created a medical and financial burden for Tom & Lori Jarosik-Carroll-our brother, sister, son, daughter and friends. For this reason, we have organized a benefit to be held Sunday, February 26th 2017 to honor and support Hannah and help raise funds for her continuing medical needs. We will have tons of entertainment including live bands and irish dancing as well as raffles and silent auctions.

If you cannot make the fundraiser and would still like to donate, please click on the link below or email us at hannahstrong2017@gmail.com. We are looking for any/all type of donations for our basket/silent auctions.

title: Ben Rector @ Good Vibrations Music Fest | The 1850 Settlement | 4pm-12am
description:
Bringing together the hearing world with the deaf/hard-of-hearing community. Aid the Silent, a San Antonio-based nonprofit organization that benefits the deaf and hard-of-hearing (HOH) community,  will host the first known fully deaf/HOH-accessible music and arts festival May 20, 2017 at the 1850 Settlement in San Antonio, TX. The Good Vibrations Music & Arts festival (GVMAF) presented by industry leaders in hearing solutions, Cochlear Americas, Ear Institute of Texas, and GN ReSound, will feature live captioning, ASL interpretation, T-coiling, front row seating, vibrating backpacks and a visual light show, which will sync to performances for a true sensory experience.

Funds raised from this event will benefit Aid the Silent's four branches: deaf resources, deaf education, deaf ministry and deaf research. As part of the nonprofit's mission to break down barriers associated with hearing loss, GVMAF will bring together the hearing world with the deaf/HOH community. Aid the Silent provides children and teens the tools and resources they need to find personal success, whether that be through assistive hearing devices, hearing aids, speech therapy, learning ASL or camps and events. The music and arts festival will feature area food trucks, artisan's market, photo booths, crafts and games. 

For more info contact info@goodvibrationsmusicfest.com.

Visit us online at goodvibrationsmusicfest.com

OSHA 10 General Industry Course TopicsThis 10-hour safety course is geared for general industry employees, which includes all employees not in the construction, maritime, or agricultural fields. Many employers in such fields as building maintenance, warehouse assembly, and security prefer to hire candidates already holding the OSHA 10 General certification.

OSHA 10-Hour General Industry -- Designated Training Topics.This training program is intended to provide entry level general industry workers information about their rights, employer responsibilities, and how to file a complaint as well as how to identify, abate, avoid, and prevent job related hazards on a job site. The training covers a variety of general industry safety and health hazards which a worker may encounter. Training will emphasize hazard identification, avoidance, control, and prevention, not OSHA standards.

OSHA mandates that the 10 hours of training be broken into 7 hours of mandatory topics, 2 hours of elective topics, and 1 hour of optional topics as follows:

Mandatory - 7 hoursIntroduction to OSHA -- 2 hoursCovers workers' rights, employer responsibilities, and how to file a complaint. It includes helpful worker safety and health resources. It also provides samples of a weekly fatality and 3 catastrophe report, material data safety sheet, and the OSHA Log of Work-Related Injuries and Illnesses.

Walking and Working Surfaces, including fall protection -- 1 hourCovers trip hazards and considerations of different surfaces that employees may have to walk and work on.

Exit Routes, Emergency Action Plans, Fire Prevention Plans, and Fire Protection -- 1 hourCovers emergency evacuation procedures and routes.

Electrical -- 1 hourCovers electrical hazards and the dangers involved with working with electrical equipment.

Personal Protective Equipment -- 1 hourCovers the proper, effective use of personal protective equipment (such as hearing protection, safety goggles, and gloves), including statistics of injuries related to the failure to properly use personal protective equipment

Hazard Communication -- 1 hourCovers the proper way to label and catalogue hazardous materials and chemicals, such as cleaners and photocopier toner cartridges.

Elective - 2 hoursThe instructor will teach two to four of the following topics:

Hazardous MaterialsCovers safety considerations involving potentially harmful chemicals or objects.

Materials HandlingCovers diverse operations such as hoisting tons of steel with a crane, driving a truck loaded with concrete blocks, manually carrying bags and material, and stacking drums, barrels, kegs, lumber, or loose bricks.

Machine GuardingCovers safety risks related to any moving parts of machines on premises. This topic is most common to industrial or MAKING work places which have such as a printing press or assembly line.

Introduction to Industrial HygieneIndustrial hygiene is the science of anticipating, recognizing, evaluating, and controlling workplace conditions that may cause workers' injury or illness. Specifically, this topic covers considerations of ventilation and circulation of potentially hazardous fumes or vapors in the work place.

Bloodborne PathogensCovers the dangers associated with potential exposure to pathogenic microorganisms in the blood that could carry hepatitis B virus (HBV) and human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), among other pathogens.

ErgonomicsThis topic teaches how the use of Ergonomics, which is fitting a job to a person, helps lessen muscle fatigue, increase productivity, and reduce the number and severity of work-related musculoskeletal disorders.

Safety and Health ProgramCovers topics for consideration for creating, implementing, and enforcing your own workplace Safety and Health Programs

Fall ProtectionCovers ways to protect workers against fall hazards. This topic is particularly useful to industries with heightened fall dangers, such as stage actors or lighting technicians.

Optional - 1 hourThere is also an hour reserved for optional safety training. We can tailor an additional topic to a specific client (such as water safety if the client is a school with a swimming pool), or what most often happens is this hour is reserved for any of the previous topics that the students are particularly engaged in and want to spend more than the allotted time on. It is often helpful for the instructor to have this hour at his or her disposal to be able to devote to any topic in which the students are especially engaged.

All paid fees will be applicable towards the next session. Start date of new session must be within 6 months of start date of previous session. If session price increases, student is responsible for paying the difference. If that session is on waitlist, student will be added to end of waitlist. If student’s name does not come up within 6 months, paid fees are non-refundable.

If student decides three or more days after the first class of a session to transfer to another session, the transfer will be permitted at the discretion of the administrators and will be subject to the following conditions: an additional deposit to hold their spot in the next session will be required. 50% of previously paid fees will be applicable towards the next session. Start date of new session must be within 6 months of start date of previous session. If session price increases, student is responsible for paying the difference. title: Peak District Day Hike
description:
Peak District Day Hike *£19 until the 26th January, £25 thereafter*

The beautiful Peak District National Park, full of rugged charm, stone villages and dramatic views of the rolling countryside.

Our hike takes us through part of the famous Edale skyline route, allowing you to experience the beautiful scenery of wild moorland plateaus and Edale valley.

Find similar trips at:

http://www.adventurelust.co.uk


	
	

Adventurelust Day Trips

These are trips that are open to beginners/intermediates with a good level of fitness. Each trip varies in difficulty however, depending on the terrain, time of year and chosen routes.

All day and classic trips and routes are extensively planned, with alternate and contingency plans in the event of adverse weather conditions or unforeseen circumstances. Given the nature of the trip anything could happen and itineraries could change, therefore we ask you to be adaptable and open minded when booking trips.

What's Involved?

• Day hike in the Peaks

• Build your own weekend around this day hike or visit and return in a day

• Summit of Kinder Scout (the highest point in the Peak District)

• See Kinder Downfall (the highest waterfall in the Peak District)

• A stunning view of Ringing Roger

• Optional stay for drinks and meal in a local pub with an open fire

• Toughness: Please note: the walks on this trip are strenuous and require a good level of fitness.

























What's Included?

• Guided hike

• An organised social day with like minded people who want to get out and explore parts of the UK

What's not Included?

• Travel to/from the meeting point

• Any local transportation costs

• Costs of a personal nature













What to Bring

• Appropriate walking clothes and hiking footwear (ideally hiking boots). Waterproof jacket, trousers and footwear are recommended

• Water (at least 1 and ideally 2 litres)

• Packed lunch/picnic

• Money for drinks and refreshments after the walk

See the kit list here:

– Adventurelust Kit list (https://www.adventurelust.co.uk/recommeded-kit-list)

Price & Payment

£19 Early Bird until Jan 27th

£25 Standard price from Jan 28th

Payments are non-refundable and non-transferable

Transport & Meeting

We'll meet at Penny Pot Cafe at 10am prompt (Station Approach, Edale S33 7ZA). You will need transport to get you to this location and back home afterwards.

Planned end time at 5pm to 6pm.

Click here for a Street view of our meeting point: https://goo.gl/JrznBn

Or here for a map: https://goo.gl/r2OVGQ

Difficulty

Strenuous

Rating: 7/10

Ascent:  636m

Terrain: Mix of tarmac, gravel, muddy farm land, stone paths and bog.

Walking time: About 5 to 6 hours of actual walking

Lunch & Drinks

There will be opportunities to stop and have your own snacks and drinks during the hikes, please ensure you bring snacks and drink with you.

SAFETY AND TERMS & CONDITIONS

Your safety is very important to us. A First Aid kit is carried and the hike organiser is first aid qualified and has experience of hiking difficult terrain in the UK and abroad.

Payments are non-refundable and non transferable.

By signing up to this event you agree to the Terms and Conditions and Acknowledgment of Risk here:

– Adventurelust Terms & Conditions (http://adventurelust.co.uk/terms-conditions/)

– Acknowledgment of Risk (http://adventurelust.co.uk/acknowledgement-of-risk/)

Hills and Mountain Danger

There can be sheer drops off of hiking trails in the mountains, stone paths can be extremely slippery particularly going down, mist and clouds can suddenly appear and infringe visibility and sunlight disappears a lot faster when surrounded by mountains. At this time of year the Lake District is unusually full of snow and ice, making hiking trails far more difficult to navigate.

Whether you're part of an organised group or exploring in your own free time, always be aware of the conditions, wear suitable clothing, leave enough time to complete the journey and take care not to take unnecessary risks putting yourself or others in danger.

Personal travel insurance is strongly recommend - The British Mountaineering Council offer a comprehensive travel insurance package at a good price here:

- BMC Travel Insurance (https://www.thebmc.co.uk/insurance).

Or alternatively you can search for insurance that covers the activities above.

© Adventurelust Ltd 2016. Errors and Omissions Excepted

Aaron Dontez Yates, better known as Tech N9ne, is an American rapper, songwriter, record producer, actor, and entrepreneur. In 1999, he and business partner Travis O'Guin founded the record label Strange Music. He has sold over two million albums and has had his music featured in film, television, and video games. In 2009, he won the Left Field Woodie award at the mtvU Woodie Awards.

His stage name originated from the TEC-9 semi-automatic handgun, a name given to him by rapper Black Walt due to his fast rhyming Chopper style. description:
Cultivating Compassion through Communication
Life changing language skills for connection and collaboration
NVC Workshop for everyone at all levels   
March 11/12, 2016 in Calgary
*SPECIAL: TWO TICKETS FOR $299*



Explore the power of NVC or Compassionate Communication

Speak with clarity in a way more likely to be heard by others
Learn and experience the transformative skills of Self Empathy
 Untangle your stories and express what really matters to Connect
Enhance relationships at home, at work, and in community

Celebrate, support, and have fun being part of a growing community


Lead Workshop Presenters:
This year we are delighted to have the wonderful CNVC Certified Anne Walton bringing her years of experience to join always insightful host/lead facilitator Al Tinholt.  We also have  a team of NVC supporters/facilitators supporting us during concurrent sessions.



Anne Walton 

Certified Trainer with the Center for Nonviolent Communication (CNVC)

http://chooseconnection.com,

annewalton43@gmail,com

613 204 8824

Anne is thrilled to have found her way to Marshall Rosenberg’s work and is deeply grateful for the enormous difference these tools have made in her life. Sharing NVC with others brings a deep sense of fulfillment, meaning and purpose. Over the past 11 years, Anne has shared NVC with thousands in Canada, the US and South Korea, at in-person trainings, through teleclasses and on TV.  Participants enjoy her authenticity, warmth, clarity and humour.  She is well known and well love in our compassionate communication community!





Al Tinholt 
P. Eng, Founder LOH (Language of the Heart

Al Tinholt on Facebook - like this page to see other events
altinholt@gmail.com

tel:1-403-609-7229

Al Tinholt brings an inviting compassionate presence to our event.  He is quick to step out of the theory to demonstrate with poetic ease... this is what it sounds like!  Music to the ears!

A husband, father, community leader, facilitator/coach, and a long time consultant and CEO. His special interest in transformative communication took root in 1994 when he worked with youth peer support in service programs.  In 1995 he co-founded an outdoor experiential leadership experience in the backcountry of the Canadian Rocky Mountains. He also created a popular workshop series called Language of the Heart (LOH).  He completed NVC international intensive training with NVC founder Marshall Rosenberg, is a member of the CNVC Trainer Community Certification Program  and among other qualifications is certified as Grief Recovery Specialist.

His passion for compassionate communication, conflict transformation, restorative circles and conscious leadership has brought him to lead in diverse settings. He facilitatex individual edu-therapy, couples co-counselling, community practice groups, treaty 7 workshops, women's correctional facilities, social services ngo's, and Alberta health services/regional public school initiatives to name a few,

Al is also a professionally registered, award winning biological/environmental engineering consultant with extensive experience facilitating multi-stakeholder groups, chairing leadership and advocacy committees, technical forums, strategic planning sessions and corporate board tables!

What participants are saying:

	Al you are an amazing facilitator, listener and support…. I most enjoyed watching you pulling out words from our 'stories' finding meaning in what each person said/shared. So many layers and so fascinating!  Keen to see what we can incorporate further…-  MW, Project Coordinator Mental Health Capacity Building for Children and Families
	Thank-you for your leadership and teaching and your mindful pauses and your intentional breaths and most of all your humility. You get this stuff deeply and that is easily noticed in you!- Rev. E.A.H Calvary Lutheran Parish
	Hi Al, Just wanted to share how connecting and inspiring it was for me see your empathy skills. Seeing you connect with people it really demonstrated to me what it is like to live NVC. I guess it had been a while since I had seen someone really live it. So inspiring. - PC. NVC Trainer Candidate

Calgary AB. (Note exact address may change based on registrations)

Before January 31 - $195

Registration below


Inspiration & Resources
Learn more about Dr. Marshall Rosenberg (1934-2015) Founder of Nonviolent Communication, NVC.

Marshall Rosenberg on Wikipedia

Nonviolent Communication on Wikipedia



Nonviolent Communication: A Language of Life, Life-Changing Tools for Healthy Relationships 
by Marshall B. Rosenberg
Get the book on Amazon

Do you hunger for skills to improve the quality of your relationships, to deepen your sense of personal empowerment or to simply communicate more effectively? Unfortunately, for centuries our culture has taught us to think and speak in ways that can actually perpetuate conflict, internal pain and even violence. Nonviolent Communication partners practical skills with a powerful consciousness and vocabulary to help you get what you want peacefully.

In this internationally acclaimed text, Marshall Rosenberg offers insightful stories, anecdotes, practical exercises and role-plays that will dramatically change your approach to communication for the better. Discover how the language you use can strengthen your relationships, build trust, prevent conflicts and heal pain. Revolutionary, yet simple, NVC offers you the most effective tools to reduce violence and create peace in your life—one interaction at a time.

“I define connection as the energy that exists between people when they feel seen, heard, and valued; when they can give and receive without judgment; and when they derive sustenance and strength from the relationship.” ― Brené Brown

title: Black Gold: BLACK BELT JONES
description:
7:30 pm - BLACK GOLD pre-show 8:00 pm - Movie starts! Join us this February for The Royal Cinema’s newest screening series, BLACK GOLD. Celebrating the best and campiest of black cinema and its heroes from then ‘til now, Black Gold’s inaugural film is BLACK BELT JONES and is co-presented by KUNG-FU FRIDAYS.

Directed by Robert Clouse and starring Jim Kelly, both fresh off of Enter the Dragon, 1974’s Black Belt Jones gives its black heroes center stage. Kelly stars at the titular Jones and is tasked with saving local legend Pop Byrd’s karate school from the predatory business interests of the city’s quickly encroaching mafia and drug-dealing associates. Joined by Byrd’s students and daughter (played by a show-stealing, ball-busting Gloria Hendry), Jones kicks ass and is not here for any white nonsense.

A perfect blend of martial arts and blaxploitation, the film offers Jones and Hendry as the archetypal, community-minded heroes we’ve come to know from the surge of blaxploitation cinema which followed. While critically maligned at the time in the shadow of Enter the Dragon’s success, Black Belt Jones clearly stands on its own - it's all-black and all-kitsch, baby. Come for Jim Kelly, stay for the indeterminately extended car wash fight scene.

Generously sponsored by Loveless Cafe & Bar.
