title: Challenge Course and Climbing Program Management
description:
Course Description

*This is an advanced level course and requires participants to submit a course application and portfolio to complete the registration process. Details will be sent via email upon initial registration.

The 30 hour Ropes Course and Climbing
Program Management training course is designed to help senior adventure program
instructors and program directors manage their ropes course and climbing
programs (tower, wall, or cliff) more effectively. This 30 hour training will
enhance your ability to deliver safe and effective adventure programs by increasing
your understanding of standards, current research and testing, emergency
preparedness and program assessment. The workshop’s experiential approach
enables leadership teams to refine their ropes course and climbing program
management systems and hone their critical incident response plan.

Course Objectives

By the end of this training, ropes course and climbing program management attendees will:


	Appreciate how current standards and practices may inform the operation of ropes courses and climbing programs
	Have the ability to improve their adventure program’s effectiveness by applying research findings, assessment, and evaluation tools
	Apply the key concepts of the injury counter-measures model to their own safety management plan 
	Create more effective management systems for their adventure program using the tools provided in their site’s operations manual 
	Understand the implications of recent research and testing on equipment selection, facility operations, and staff training


We offer two tracks for this training - Certification and Audit. Choose the track that is right for you:

Audit



The skills and concepts taught in the Ropes Course and Climbing Program Management training course are of benefit to any director or program director having supervisory responsibility for the adventure programming aspect at their facility. As such, we provide an “audit” opportunity for those who do not meet the certification pre-requisites. Participants who are “auditing” may participate fully in all aspects of the training, but will not be eligible to participate in the Testing Day. As such their participation will be complete at the end of Day 3.

Certification


	Those individuals who meet the prerequisites for
certification, complete all the course hours, and successfully complete the
practical skills assessment and written test will receive certification as a
Challenge Course Manager, in accordance with ACCT Standards.


	Prerequisites:


	21 years of age
	500 documented hours of
adventure program delivery and management experience
	
	Current certification
as a Level 2 Challenge Course Practitioner (Adventureworks! Associates, Inc. Ropes
Course Instructor or equivalent)
	
	
	Willingness and ability
to perform all tasks related to ropes course and climbing wall operation
including spotting, belaying, climbing on belay, climbing on personal fall
protection to perform set-up / take-down, and performing in-air rescue tasks
	
	


Additional Info:


	Please ensure that you have read and understood the Registration Policies.
	
	If choosing "Course Only" option, course participants are responsible for their own accommodation for the duration of the course. Meals are included in all options.
	Meals include lunch on first day of course, to lunch on last day. 
	This event leads to ACCT Certification.  Please read the Certification FAQ's.
	NEW! Organizations may purchase course seats without registering specific individuals. Registration "tickets" can be transferred at any time to an individual within your organization.
	Taxes and fees including in pricing.

description:
2017 is bringing expanded programming to the Women in Tech Summit - Philadelphia!

We will be offering a half day of workshops on Friday, April 21st and our full day conference on Saturday, April 22nd.  You can purchase a ticket to attend Friday only, Saturday only or both Friday and Saturday.



The Women in Tech Summit  inspires, educates and connects women in the technology industry. Our goal is to support the community of women currently working in technology and to help pave the way for women and young women who want to enter the industry.

The Women in Tech Summit is the only women in technology conference that provides attendees with a unique combination of deep-dive, hands-on tech workshops; information and discussions about careers in tech and how to pursue them; and connection and networking opportunities with other women in various aspects and careers in technology. title: Event & Meeting Management Fundamentals | NYC
description:
Event Planning Pro or Novice? Take our free online assessment test to see if you make the grade.

Here
 you'll get a thorough understanding of how events work, why people and 
companies host events, how the industry is configured, and how to 
strategically plan and coordinate a typical event from A to Z. This 
course will cover the role of events in today's world, budgets and 
goals, workflow management, venue selection and negotiation, room 
layouts and seating formats, food and beverage, entertainment and 
speakers, design and decor, transportation and logistics, registration 
and check-in, hybrid meetings, apps and technology, basic lighting and 
audio visual, and more. 
	Course StructureHybrid 
courses blend the best elements of online and in person learning. Prior 
to class each week, you'll view the lesson video modules online in our 
private learning management system. Then you'll meet in person each week
 where your instructor will lead the group in applying the concepts 
learned online, through interactive discussions, group exercises, case 
studies, guest speakers, field trips and other interactive elements.
	Dates/TimesThis 10-week hybrid course blends online lectures and weekly in-person meetings. Case Studies of Major EventsWhen
 you meet in person your instructor will lead the group in discussing 
key concepts learned online through case studies of high profile events,
 such as major conventions, product launches, awards shows, fundraising 
galas, fashion shows, thought leader conferences and more.
	Guest SpeakersAs
 part of the in-person experience, you'll meet several prominent guest 
speakers from the industry who will share their insights, explain how 
they produced major events, answer questions, and provide job tips. The 
specific names will be posted shortly. Previous speakers have been 
senior leaders from: Google, Bank of America, BizBash, Proscenium, BKA, 
Elizabeth Rose Consulting, David Stark Design & Production, Social 
Tables, and others.
	Behind the Scenes Field TripsDuring
 the course your instructor will lead the group on behind-the-scenes 
field trips to major venues, caterers, production companies, designers, 
live events, and others. You'll meet leaders on site who'll explain what
 their companies do, how they do it, and share best practices for you to
 work with them in the most cost-effective way possible. Specific field 
trips for this course will be posted shortly.

title: Music 4.5 – The Economics of Streaming
description:
The Economics of Streaming…and the ‘value gap’
Consumption of streaming music, media and entertainment is exploding around the world. Free, ad-supported music services are reaching millions of users who want to listen to what they want, when they want. Since the creation of the first paid subscription services 15 years ago, the labels have considered on-demand access to be consumption - not promotion - eventually competing with and replacing the lucrative sales model their businesses were built on.

Today the largest music service in the world is YouTube, with 1billion monthly active users. Over 58% of Internet users in the U.S. have a YouTube account. Facebook has 1.71bn monthly active users (with more than 1bn daily active users on mobile); Twitter has 320mm, and Spotify has 100mm. Contrast these user numbers withthe paying subscriber numbers of Apple Music, now at over 20 million subscribers, and Spotify with 40 million paying subscribers.

YouTube stars are garnering vast audiences and enviable revenue, while music artists and the music industry are increasingly frustrated that they are not receiving comparable value for the use of their music and compositions. They argue that YouTube isn’t a revenue generator commensurate with its user base. New consumption patterns and a specific video and YouTube culture have emerged, which in conjunction with the existing Safe Harbor legislation, is changing the relationship between fan, star and revenue-generation

Siding with the record industry over the amount of money YouTube pays to artists and labels Andrus Ansip, VP for the Digital Single Market at the European Commission, estimates that YouTube now contributes $679m a year to music rights-holders, despite its billion-plus monthly audience, while Spotify alone delivers $1.8bn.

Meanwhile, in the last twelve months, YouTube has paid out over $1 billion to the music industry from advertising alone. Unlike the audio streaming services, YouTube won’t commit to pay minimum guarantees based on users and usage, but it will share ad income with music rights owners, meaning that income to the music industry goes up as more ads are sold, not more videos streamed.

What are the economics of streaming – for the service providers, the rightsholders, the artists and the users?

If ad-supported and subscription services are increasingly competing head-on, should free services be paying the same percentage of their income to rights holders as paid subscription services? What is the impact of the DMCA Safe Harbor provision on revenue for rights holders?

What changes in legislation, licensing and contracts will guarantee a marketplace where the two different business models - free, ad-supported and paid-for subscription - can be made to work “fairly” with increased revenues returned to artists and rightsholders?

Music 4.5 The Economics of Streaming will examine the economics and business models of streaming, the latest developments around music licensing, the implications of digital service providers different business models, legislative reform, as well as the impact of the ad-market dynamics on per-stream rates for artists, record labels, publishers, and collective rights management organizations.

We will cover questions such as:


	How can the ‘free model’ be made to work better and more fairly for artists? 
	Will the review of safe harbor legislation deliver a level playing field between ad-supported and subscription-based service providers, e.g. Spotify and YouTube? 
	Will ‘take down’ also mean ‘stay down’? What are the issues with ‘stay down?’ How accurate is YouTube’s Content ID?
	How to grow the pie by opening up for additional royalties collection? What are the additional but currently neglected and untapped revenue streams, e.g. performance royalties for terrestrial radio? 
	Everyone mentions YouTube, but how about the other big platform and social networks, like Facebook and Twitter, which are increasingly focused on video content delivery? Will they also rely on the DMCA Safe Harbor for user-uploaded content, or will they negotiate agreements with labels and publishers? What is the potential impact for artists and the music business? 
	How do artists, rightsholders, and users navigate multi-territory licensing? 
	Is it the government’s role to legislate rates to guarantee a competitive marketplace? 

If consumption is free, what is the value of promotion?

title: I AM Initiative Girl Scout Event
description:
The foundation of the I Am Initiative is based on Think —> Feel —> Act. The guiding message is self-protection through self-love.

Girl Scout Events are 2-hour workshops designed to dynamically teach the 3 rules of self-protection. The girls learn cool kickboxing moves as well as practical tools to live confidently and powerfully in the world. All workshops include earning a fun self-protection badge.


THINK: I AM STRONG (My thoughts guide my attitude)
What you think is who you are. The first rule of self-protection is: F.L.Y.(FIRST LOVE YOURSELF). Strong self-esteem allows you to take care of yourself and be kind to others because you know who you are and how to express yourself confidently.


FEEL: I AM CONFIDENT (My attitude guides my actions)
The I Am Initiative teaches girls to stay out of proximity of any situation where they are endangered, while challenging them to face their fears. When you trust yourself you are confident and are able to stand up for what you feel is right. In uncomfortable scenarios you will be able to trust your gut and follow the second rule of self-defense: FACE YOUR FEARS. RUN AWAY FROM DANGER.


ACT: I AM POWERFUL (My actions create my reality)
What you do is intricately connected to what you think and how you feel. The third rule of self-defense is: BE POSITIVE CHANGE. Conduct yourself with responsibility, authority, and act powerfully according to what you believe and you will have a positive impact in the world and be able to protect yourself.

title: MDFF: SHORT STAY
description:
Multi-hyphenate Ted Fendt delivers on the promise of his acclaimed short films without sacrificing an ounce of his singular charm and rigor. Shooting on 16mm (blown up to 35mm), the writer-director-editor here focuses on Mike (Mike MacCherone), an ambitionless resident of Haddonfield, New Jersey, who finds himself subletting a friend’s room in Philadelphia and (ineptly) covering his shifts at a by-donation walking-tour company. Mike floats, as if in a trance, from one low-key comic folly to another, each one a strange and subtle moral tale. Fendt’s economy of expression, expert handling of his nonprofessional cast, and incomparable nose for the tragicomic dimension of the everyday distinguishes Short Stay as a truly anomalous work in contemporary American cinema: a film made entirely on its maker’s terms.

""This is slacker cinema for people who can't even be bothered to light a joint — in its own strange way a marvelous thing." — Calum Marsh, The Village Voice"This stripped-down story of a less-than-dynamic man lets its gentle humor tip over into the excruciating again and again, functioning like a finely tuned moral tale whose tenderness for its characters doesn't mean it won't expose their shortcomings." — James Lattimer, Slant

 

"Short Stay does not feel like a bigger film than director Ted Fendt's charmingly ill-fitting shorts, but rather is a more robust, fuller in passing detail and commonplace incident. In other words: unassuming, but charged." — Daniel Kasman, MUBI Notebook

title: Caring for Your Fruit and Nut Trees
description:
This class gives you the tools that you need to grow healthy fruit and nut trees for years to come.  Kim Knox, a certified arborist, makes the class fun.  Fruit and nut trees provide healthy food, shade, habitat for birds and butterflies, and beauty to our homes and communities.  But most fruit and nut trees require special care.
   This class has been approved for 5 International Society of Arboriculture (ISA) credits.

In this class, you will learn the basics of planting and taking care of fruit trees in your yard, school or community.  We learn how to take care of apples, plums, persimmon, cherry, serviceberry, pawpaw, hazelnut, walnut and many more fruit trees.  Students will also learn how to prune fruit trees, use integrated pest management to take care of harmful bugs, and care for your fruit trees in order to enjoy their fruit for years to come.

title: The Power of Positive,  Inspiring Solutions
description:
Judging by Guy’s experience speaking in high schools, the new generation, following Gen X and the Millennials, is Gen W - Generation Worry. When he asks students: “When you think about the future of our world, what do you feel - Hope, or Worry?” Very few hands go up for “hope”—almost all go up for “worry”. Our need as educators is to generate hope - to turn Gen W into Gen H.

The webinar will showcase the power of positive, inspiring solutions to the worries that are causing so many young people to lose hope, including the climate crisis, the wider ecological crisis, which includes the oceans filling up with plastic, and larger economic and political worries. It will show how, using a positive three-step approach, you can turn worry into hope, and then into action.

Guy Dauncey is a futurist who works to develop a positive vision of a sustainable future, and to translate that vision into action. He is founder of the BC Sustainable Energy Association, which developed the successful middle-school program the Climate Change Showdown. He is the author or co-author of ten books, including The Climate Challenge: 101 Solutions to Global Warming and Journey to the Future: A Better World Is Possible. He is an Honorary Member of the Planning Institute of BC, and a Fellow of the Royal Society for the Arts. His websites are www.earthfuture.com, www.journeytothefuture.ca and www.thepracticalutopian.ca. He lives on Vancouver Island, in British Columbia.

title: Robots vs Unicorns: DARK STAR
description:
Made for just $55,000 and shot (and re-shot) over the course of three and half years, DARK STAR began life as final year thesis film by a pair of angry young USC film students named John Carpenter and Dan O'Bannon. A decade before they redefined cinematic horror and science-fiction, Carpenter and O'Bannon collaborated on this messy, anarchic, counter-culture counterpunch to the candy-coated imperialism of STAR TREK and sterile, cerebral distance of 2001: A SPACE ODYSSEY. Instead of brave astronauts boldly going beyond the infinite, the crew of this titular space vessel are a bunch of crabby, bored and antisocial misfits. And rather than explore the strange new worlds they seek out, they just blow them up (aided by inexplicably sentient -- and hilariously enthusiastic -- thermostellar bombs).

Already settling into career-defining roles, Carpenter and O'Bannon colloborated on the witty, subversive screenplay, with Carpenter handling directing duties and composing the electronic score (his farty bass tracks are a highlight, though miles from the elegant simplicity that would soon become his sonic trademark). O'Bannon edited and contributed to the clever, if primitive, special effects, and, most memorably, played the central role of the hapless Sgt. Pinback.

The student film found its way into the hands of producer Jack Harris (THE BLOB), who felt it had commercial potential and asked for re-shoots to bring it up to feature length. Owing as much to the practicality of O'Bannon's presence as to creative choice, most of the reshoots centered around expanding Sgt. Pinback's misadventures with the ship's extraterrestrial mascot, a mischevious beachball alien (puppeteered by fellow USC alumni Nick Castle, later Michael Myers in HALLOWEEN and director of THE LAST STARFIGHTER).

Despite Harris' instincts, DARK STAR was not a great success ("We went from having the most impressive student film ever made to the least impressive commercial film ever made," O'Bannon would later say), and Carpenter and O'Bannon parted creative company shortly afterward (on less-than-friendly terms, if Jason Zinoman's book SHOCK VALUE is to believed).

Regardless, both would soon find massive individual success in DARK STAR's wake. Fellow USC grad George Lucas was sufficiently impressed with O'Bannon's work to hire him as a special effects artist on STAR WARS. Carpenter had a moderate hit with ASSAULT ON PRECINCT 13, which of course led to HALLOWEEN, which at the time became the highest grossing independent film ever made. O'Bannon went from STAR WARS to Alejandro Jodorowsky's doomed adaptation of DUNE (where he first made the acquaintance of Swiss artist H.R. Giger) and channeled his frustrations with DARK STAR's threadbare production values and lacklustre reception into his screenplay STARBEAST, later renamed ALIEN, launching a game-changing film franchise that continues literally to this day.

Join us at The Royal for a very rare chance to see this low-fi sci-fi counter-culture cult classic on the big screen!

title: Kombucha and Raw Apple Cider Vinegar Workshop.
description:
They are called “sister ferments.” Raw vinegar and kombucha ferment very similarly, the latter being effervescent and slightly sweet. One of the most popular among the fermented beverages, kombucha is a sugar-sweetened tea fermented by a culture of living organisms called a SCOBY (symbiotic colony of bacteria and yeast.) This tonic is akin to raw vinegar.

Raw vinegar is used to aid detoxification, to add as a sour flavor in foods, for cleaning and much more. It alkalizes our bodies and can be used as a remedy for a wide array of ailments or conditions. An acetic acid ferment, raw vinegar is simple to make. Yet commercially, it is almost always deprived of its live culture benefits.

We will learn about home brewing kombucha for beginners, plus dive into the art of second fermentation, techniques and methods to get your brew at its best. We will also learn how to make raw apple cider vinegar, which requires nothing more than apples and pure water. Live kombucha cultures will be available for you to take home, plus home brewing instructions to get your first batch going. Participants will also be able to taste all of our fermented food and beverages, all made locally. Space is limited, so be sure to sign up by February 13, 2017.

title: ‘Precious Relics’: Hair Jewellery and the Victorians
description:
Evening Talk at the Florence Nightingale Museum 

The zeal with which men adopted beards and whiskers in the 19th century is surely matched by the Victorians’ enthusiasm for wearing jewellery containing human hair. Everyone, it seems - from Queen Victoria herself to Florence Nightingale and the serving men of the Crimea - understood the ‘sacred worth’ of a lock of hair from the head of a loved one.

Drawing on material in the Florence Nightingale Museum and other public and private collections, artist Jane Wildgoose considers a wealth of intricately crafted watch-chains, lockets, necklaces, bracelets and rings containing human hair, and the ways in which these ‘precious relics’ spoke of ties of love, kinship, and loss during the Victorian era.
Admission price for all talks £8.00 (Members of the Florence Nightingale Museum FREE) and includes a glass of wine and a chance to view the museum. Doors will be open from 6pm, for a 6:30pm start.


                                                                                                                                                                        This lecture is part of our season of events for 'The Age of the Beard,' an exhibition and series of events generously funded by the Wellcome Trust.

They decided to break the fetters that connected them almost exclusively to "Dubstep" and started using other forms of expression. It is therefore with their new album "Hybrid Distillery" that the group now has to make an impression by imposing its style in other genres of electronic music. This fifth album is not only another acoustic chapter, it is also about graphics. The draftsman/graffiti artist/director "Ebola - Delit2fuite" brings a whole new visual world mixed with, just like Ganja White Night, artistic originality and singularity never achieved until now.

title: Jerry Buting Presents ILLUSION OF JUSTICE w/ Robert Kolker
description:
Please join us at WORD Jersey City for a reading, discussion, and Q&A with one of the minds being Making of a Murder, Jerome Buting, to celebrate his new book THE ILLUSION OF JUSTICE. Buting will be joined in conversation by Robert Kolker of Bloomberg News.

The TV documentary phenomenon Making of a Murder, which debuted on Netflix in December 2015, explores the story of Steven Avery, a man from Manitowoc County, Wisconsin, who served 18 years in prison for the wrongful conviction of sexual assault and attempted murder of Penny Beerntsen, before being fully exonerated in 2003 by DNA evidence.  In 2005, Avery was arrested on charges of murdering Teresa Halbach, a local photographer, and convicted in 2007. Jerome F. Buting, who has served as a high-profile criminal defense attorney for 35 years, defended Avery in the murder trial. Despite his best efforts, and those of co-counsel Dean Strang, Avery was found guilty of first-degree intentional homicide and sentenced to life in prison in March 2007. 

Not since The Thin Blue Line has there been a true crime documentary as engrossing and provocative as Making a Murderer; Steven’s case cuts across demographic lines, and has galvanized as much debate about the integrity of our criminal justice system as it has about whether Steven Avery is guilty or innocent. In ILLUSION OF JUSTICE: Inside Making a Murderer and America’s Broken System (Harper, 2/28/2017), Buting provides an insider’s riveting narrative of the Avery case and that of his nephew, Brendan Dassey—and what the cameras did not capture—interwoven with the story of his own development as a criminal defense lawyer; as he reflects on his professional motivations and discusses other career-defining cases (including another, equally shocking wrongful conviction that he worked on with The Innocence Project), he provides commentary on the integrity of our law enforcement and legal systems. Together, his experiences shape a relevant analysis of the deeply flawed judicial system in which he practices.

Robert Kolker is the New York Times bestselling author of Lost Girls: An Unsolved American Mystery, a narrative-nonfiction chronicle of unsolved murder that was named one of the New York Times’ 100 Notable Books and one of Publisher's Weekly’s Top Ten Books of the year. An award-winning investigative journalist, he currently is a Projects & Investigations reporter for Bloomberg News.

Jerome F. Buting is a shareholder in the Brookfield, Wisconsin law firm of Buting, Williams & Stilling, S.C. He received his undergraduate degree in Forensic Studies from Indiana University and his law degree from the University of North Carolina–Chapel Hill. He is a past board director of the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, a past president of the Wisconsin Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, and chair of the Wisconsin State Bar Criminal Law Section from 2005 to 2007. His present private practice is entirely criminal defense, both trials and appeals. He has defended the citizen accused in many serious high profile trial cases, including the Steven Avery case, and he obtained the reversal of convictions in State of Wisconsin v. Ted Oswald and State of Wisconsin v. Ralph Armstrong (reversing a 25 year old murder conviction). He lectures worldwide and is frequently sought after for his knowledge in the use of expert witnesses and DNA evidence. He is also the 2016 recipient of the Fierce Advocate Award from the John Jay College of Criminal Justice.

title: 2017 Terroir Run
description:
Join us for our 7th annual Terroir Run. This 10km fun run takes place in beautiful Prince Edward County along country roads lined with vineyards, lavender fields and farm acreage.

On May 26th, the night before our run we host a Buffet BBQ at County Road Beer Co. Chef Neil Dowson will prepare a feast featuring locally grown and raised produce paired with either a pint from the brewery or a glass of sparkling from Hinterland Winery. $5 of every dinner purchase is donated to the Terry Fox Foundation. Runners can swing by to pick up their runners kits and stay for dinner or a pint.

We kick off early at 9am from the Old Third Vineyard passing 8 wineries and four water stations (yes - water, not wine). We finish off at Norman Hardie Winery where our runners and their cheering squads enjoy nutritious and delicious post-run snacks prepared by Slow Food The County, thirst quenching Pluck Teas Iced Tea and cold brewed coffee from Propeller Coffee. Once all of our runners have made it to Norm's we open the Wine, Beer & Cider Bar and start serving woodfired pizza's and fresh spring salads. There are a limited number of Post Run lunch registrations available for friends and family members who wish to join in the post run fun.

Runners are encouraged to participate in a costume for a chance to win a $200 gift certificate from Zest Kitchen Shop (in Picton) and runners up (pun intended) prizes of County wines, beer and cider. Annual proceeds from the run go to Slow Food The County and the Quinte Humane Society.

Included in your registration fee:


	Runners kit with custom Terroir Run t-shirt (Me to We)
	Post Run snacks
	Woodfired pizza lunch with wine/beer/cider at Norman Hardie Winery
	Access to shuttle services (provided to runners wishing to leave their vehicles at the finish winery. Shuttles take runners to the starting winery - The Old Third at 8am and 8:30am)

That evening (May 27th) we go "Back to the Start" with a Barn Party at The Old Third from 5pm to 10pm. Chef Jamie Kennedy will be grilling up burgers and preparing his famous fries. There will be live entertainment and a great selection of wines, beer and cider from our run partners. This is an age of majority event - 19 years or older to attend. Tickets include your meal, two drinks and entertainment.

title: SA Creates: Embroidery Workshop
description:
For this two-hour embroidery workshop, artist Dana Prieto will lead an embroidering circle open to anyone who self-identify as women (cis, trans, non-binary, etc.). Women from different ages, social and cultural backgrounds, and professions are all welcome to participate. No previous sewing experience is required. All materials will be provided including: new kitchen cloths, embroidering thread, and embroidering needles. Participants are also welcome to bring their own used or new kitchen cloth, tea towel, or dish towel to embroider. 

Embroidered pieces from this workshop can either be taken home by the participants or donated to Dana's collaborative large-scale textile installation called The Rags Between Us. 

Dana has hosted and facilitated three embroidering circles where she collaborated with over 100 women to embroider old and new cloths while engaging in a deeply enriching experience, sharing time, labour, and conversations. In each occasion, our old rags and our most dear female relationships and narratives have been our muses of inspiration.

About the FacilitatorDana Prieto is an Argentine artist and educator based in Toronto. She completed a BFA in Drawing and Painting at OCAD University.

Her work circles around the mundane through the creation of spaces, images and actions that propose uncanny participatory experiences. Using ordinary materials such as food, litter and kitchen cloths, her projects reflect on both intimate and social-political issues around migration, belonging, gender and power.

She has participated in several award-winning collaborative projects working within diverse communities in Toronto, Halifax, Buenos Aires, Rawson, Quito and Belize.



She is currently coordinating Critical Soup, an interdisciplinary food-art initiative that opens dialogues about the impacts of Canadian extractive companies in Indigenous and Global South territories.

Find out more on her website.

Image: © 2015 Dana Prieto.

For our next Trending Now event we are delighted to feature the food, drink and culture of Poland! Chef Adrian Rusyn and The Chefs’ House team will prepare a feast of traditional cuisine alongside Polish beer and — of course — vodka! We invite you to join us as we celebrate over a thousand years of history from this unique country. Na zdrowie!

About Chef Adrian Rusyn
Hailing from Głogów, Poland, Chef Adrian Rusyn has over 20 years of experience in the food & beverage industry. Since his days as an apprentice cook at Toronto’s Boulevard Club, Adrian worked in the kitchens of the Old Mill Hotel and Estates of Sunnybrook, before becoming Executive Chef at The Waterside Inn in Port Credit. In 2009, he was a recipient of the OHI’s ‘Top 30 under 30’ award, which honours rising stars in the Hospitality and Foodservice Industry. A George Brown College graduate, Adrian has  returned to his alma mater as a Chef Technologist, instructing and mentoring students at the Centre for Hospitality & Culinary Arts.

title: Blush Love Blooms: KUNDALINI, QOYA & MEDITATION WEEKEND
description:
BLUSH LOVE BLOOMS
AWAKEN THE LOVE WITHIN
26-29 MAY 2017


Blush Love Blooms is a three day love affair… with yourself.


	A blissful time dedicated to donning that much-needed oxygen mask.
	A chance to truly relax, unwind and refresh.
	A sublime time to fill your cup and celebrate all that is you.
	A remembrance of your truth - your wild, wise and free spirit.
	Re-connection to that most essential you.
	Devotion to you and the divine feminine.
	Nurturing experiences just for you.

More than a yoga retreat, Blush Love Blooms is a journey through meditation, Qoya, Kundalini yoga, ceremony and ritual. We will indulge all the senses in a feast of pure Blush Love.

The experience we have designed will envelope you in all that is self love, aimed at helping you with radical contact with your life. It is also designed with space and time for you, away from the busy every day.

Set in the luxurious surrounding of 42 Acres, you will be wrapped up and surrounded in all that is love. From award-winning food, through to sumptuous surroundings, breath-taking countryside. That’s just for starters.

You will leave the retreat feeling refreshed, restored and full of love and vitality for yourself and your world.

Find out more about us at www.blushloveretreat.com




About Blush Love Blooms hosts Kate Taylor & Gail Schock
Gail Schock
Gail Schock aka G Love is an Energy Healer, Spiritual Teacher and Self Love Revolutionary. G Love goes deeper than on-demand spirituality employing tools learned over the last decade from her formal mind, body, spirit training including Quantum Meditation, Reiki Master Teacher, Emotional Freedom Technique (Tapping), Quan Yin Magnified Healing, NLP, Coaching with Tony Robbins, Happiness Coaching and The Enneagram with Dr. Robert Holden and Kundalini yoga.

Find out more about Gail on her website www.gailschock.love



Kate Taylor
Kate Taylor has her own unique blend of Practical Magic which she will be sharing at the Blush Love Blooms. Qoya teacher, life coach and NLP Practitioner Kate helps women to connect into and explore their wild colours. With compassion, care, reverie and much sparkle, Kate holds space for you to allow your deepest truth and essence to come forward. Kate will be leading Qoya movement and Practical Magic workshops throughout the weekend.

Find out more about Kate on her website www.upcoaching.co.uk










About 42 Acres Retreat Space
42 Acres: A retreat space nestled within a secluded Somerset valley amongst Seven hundred acres of ancient forest which encircle the main house, originally built as a dairy farm in the 1800s.

A place for truth and growth.A home for those passionate about creating change. From the inside out.

Find out more at http://42acres.com/

All meals are provided by the in house chef, Mark Mabon, who has 20 years experience of cooking world foods, baking organic breads and draws on deep practical knowledge of the cleansing properties of healing whole foods, and nourishing properties of organic recipes. Everything is hand-made from fresh ingredients in the relaxed, sunny atmosphere of the farm kitchen at 42 Acres. To support the transformative process, we offer gluten free, vegetarian recipes for breakfast, lunch and dinner and any food intolerances are always catered for. Herbal teas, healthy snacks will be available throughout the day and evenings.

title: 3rd Annual Purple Pride 5K
description:
Purple Pride 5K - Saturday, February 25, 2017 - Race Start 9 am

2017 marks the start of a new era for Orlando City, as we open our new home - Orlando City Stadium - in the heart of downtown Orlando. The 3rd Annual Purple Pride 5K will start and finish at the Stadium with a post-race party in the Fanzone and a portion of the Stadium concourse. After the race, be one of the first to get a look at the rest of the Stadium during our Community Open House.

The Purple Pride 5K will be capped at maximum of 2,500 runners and each 5K participant will receive a commemorative die-cast medal after crossing the finish line. Only 2,500 runners will get their hands on this one-year-only medal that will commemorate the Stadium opening.

Each runner will also receive a race t-shirt and one ticket to a select Orlando City match during the 2017 MLS season. In addition to the stadium Open House, the post-race celebration will include a race DJ, complimentary runner refreshments,  interactive games for the entire family and discount food and beer offerings inside the stadium.

Purple Pride 5K is presented by Orlando Health, SunPass, jetBlue, Environmental Painting Alternatives and Floor & Decor. Additional partners include Publix, Academy Sports + Outdoors, Grand Bohemian Hotel and Advocare.

GENERAL INFORMATIONSaturday, February 25, 2017 – Race Start 9 amLocation: Orlando City Stadium, 655 W. Church Street, Orlando, FL 32801

Pricing Structure$32.00 until February 17$35.00 from February 18 to February 22$40.00 at Packet Pick-up on February 23 and on Race Day*Details regarding discounts available for Season Ticket Members and Lion Nation Members have been emailed. STMs can contact their guest experience representative or email tickets@orlandocitysc.com with any questions.

Entry fee and any additional match tickets purchased are non-refundable and non-transferable.

Course Map



Match Tickets & Additional Match Tickets:Each runner will receive one ticket to a select Orlando City match during the 2017 MLS season as part of this package. During the online registration process, you will have the ability to choose which match you would like to attend.

Match options include:

Wednesday, May 31, 7:30 pm vs D.C. UnitedSaturday, June 17, TBD Time vs Montreal ImpactSaturday, August 19, 7:30 pm vs. Columbus Crew

In addition, you will have the ability to purchase additional tickets to the match you choose at a discounted price of $25.

Packet Pick-Up Information & PoliciesIn addition to race day, there are 2 additional days and locations of pack pick-up for your convenience. See below for details.

You must present a form of government issued photo ID in order to pick up your packet. The only exception to this will be parents picking up packets for their children, however the parent will still need to present a photo ID.

You may pick up a packet for a friend, family member or co-worker, however you must present a written note (email or in handwriting) that indicates you have that permission AND a photocopy of that person’s government issued photo ID.

Packet Pick-Up Dates & LocationsThursday, February 234 - 7 pm, Academy Sports + Outdoors, Millenia location (3557 Gardens Ridge Way, Orlando, FL 32839)

Friday, February 2411:30 am - 2 pm, Orlando City Stadium, Southeast corner of Stadium (655 W. Church Street, Orlando, FL 32805)

Day of Event Schedule7-8:30 am – Registration & Packet Pick-up Open9 am – 5K Race Start9:15 am - 11:00 pm - Post-Race Party9 am - 1 pm - Stadium Open House10:30 am (approx.) - Awards Ceremony inside Stadium

MedalsEach finisher will receive a commemorative die-cast medal after crossing the Purple Pride 5K finish line. With the race being capped, only 2,500 runners will get their hands on this one-year-only medal that will commemorate the Stadium opening.

T-ShirtsRegistered runners will receive a race t-shirt when they pick up their packet. (sizes not guaranteed)

Timing & ScoringThe race will not be timed this year, however clocks will be placed at the start and finish so that you can keep track of your time.

AwardsTop 3 Overall Male & Female Winners receive gift cards from Publix, along with other prizes. In addition, gift cards from Academy Sports + Outdoors will be randomly distributed to race participants.

GENERAL EVENT FAQHow long is the course?The 5K is 3.1 miles.

Will the race be timed? The race will not be timed this year, however clocks will be placed at the start and finish so that you can keep track of your time.

When and where do I pick up my registration materials?See schedule above.

Who gets a T-shirt?All runners, up to 2,500, that successfully complete the registration and payment processes are guaranteed a free race t-shirt, which will be given to runners at packet pick-up. (sizes not guaranteed)

What if I need help along the way?Qualified emergency medical professionals are available to provide assistance at the start/finish lines.

Can I participate in the event with my dog?Sorry, as much as we love our pets too, the safety of participants is our main concern. Therefore, we do not allow pets on the course.

Can I participate with a stroller?Yes, nurturing future generations of runners is a priority and demonstrating healthy lifestyles to our kids is special. Please, however, start in the later part of the runners.

What do I do with my personal items while I’m running?You can leave your items in your car or have a family member watch over your personal belongings.

Should I bring my own water?Water will be provided on the course at approximately mile 1.5, as well as at the finish line.

Where do I park?Arriving 1 hour early is strongly recommended due to traffic congestion. Area parking garages available, hourly rates may apply.

For FAQs regarding match tickets, visit www.orlandocitysc.com/ockickoff/ticketFAQ.

title: The Inland Empire Fitness Conference
description:
The Inland Northwest's premier continuing education event for fitness professionals


	Our goal is to empower you through education by bringing in some of the fitness industry's top educators and fitness professionals, meeting new people and providing a fun environment in which to network.
	

**Earn up to 1.2 CEU's from NSCA, NASM, AFAA and ACE**

Pre-Conference Event (0.4 CEU's)
Friday, March 24thEvaluating and Applying Research in the Fitness Industry + VIP dinner Max of 20 attendees

12:30 PM – 1:00 PM   |   Registration

1:00 PM – 3:00 PM   |   Part 1: Evaluating Research in the Fitness Industry by James Krieger, MS

This presentation instructs students how to evaluate research in the fitness industry.

3:00 PM – 5:00 PM   |   Part 2: Applying Evidence Based Practice in the Fitness Industry by Brad Dieter, PhD

This presentation instructs students how to utilize the skills and tools of evaluating research and applying it to practice.

5:00 PM – 8:00 PM   |   VIP Dinner

_______________________________________________________________________________

Inland Empire Fitness Conference (0.8 CEU's)

Saturday, March 25th

7:15 AM – 7:45 AM   |  Registration

7:45 AM – 8:00 AM  |  Introduction

8:00 AM – 8:50 AM   |  The Effects of High-Intensity Interval Training on People with Type 2 Diabetes by April Davis, MS, ACSM-CEP, RDN

This presentation will demonstrate the current evidence to support the use of HIIT in clinical practice, and how to work with an exercise physiologist to implement or prescribe this type of training for patients who have type II diabetes.

9:00 AM – 9:50 AM   |  3 Principles to Make Strength Training More Joint Friendly by Tim Arndt, MS

This lecture will teach you the basic concepts of how to make any strength training exercise more joint friendly utilizing biomechanics to reduce joint forces.

10:00 AM – 10:50 AM   |  Bodyweight Regulation – What Really Controls the Scale by Brad Dieter, PhD

This presentation will discuss the mechanisms of body weight regulation and dissect current models and instantiate a new way of viewing body weight regulation.

11:00 AM – 11:50 AM   |  Metabolism Myth – Impact of NEAT on Body Composition by James Krieger, MS

The presentation takes the audience through the various components of energy expenditure, their roles in weight regulation, and why NEAT has by far the strongest impact.

12:00 PM – 1:00 PM   |  Catered Lunch

1:00 PM – 1:50 PM   |  Challenging the HIT Trend – Is a dose of Low-Intensity exercise Training an Ideal Physiological Prescription? by Vanessa Martinez, PhD

This lecture teaches trainers to recognize the need to find a compromise between the ideal physiological prescription and a manageable behavior prescription in order to allow adherence to be sufficient for health improvements.

2:00 PM – 2:50 PM   |  Defining Functional Training & What Makes an Exercise Functional by Tim Arndt, MS

Should we train motions or muscles? This lecture will attempt to answer that by taking a critical look at the definition of functional training and what makes an exercise functional.

3:00 PM – 3:50 PM   |  Fructose Metabolism: What the Science Really Tells Us by Brad Dieter, PhD

This presentation will discuss the role of fructose in human metabolism and how it relates to health and disease.

4:00 PM – 4:50 PM   |  The Science of Sugar – Impact of Sugar on Body Composition by James Krieger, MS

This presentation looks at the impacts of sugar intake on body composition, the history of why sugar is often blamed for obesity and addresses the potential mechanisms as to how sugar might contribute to obesity, then looks to see if there is any scientific data to support these mechanisms.

4:50 PM – 5:10 PM   |  Raffle prizes

6:00 PM – 9:00 PM   |  Dinner & Networking at Luigi’s (not required; separate charge of ~$35/person. Cash only)

*All topics are lecture and discussion based

title: TechCrunch Washington DC Meetup + Pitch-Off
description:
EVENT INFO

TechCrunch's legendary meetup + pitch-off event is coming to Washington DC! Join us for beer, good conversation, and a battle to the death to see which entrepreneurs can dazzle and excite the judges in under sixty seconds.


	Pitch-Off Competition

Participants interested in competing in the pitch-off will have 60 seconds to explain why their startup is awesome. These products must currently be in stealth or private beta. Applications are now closed.


	Office Hours

Office Hours are for companies selected to compete in the Pitch-Off. These 15 minute one-on-one talks will be held the day of the event. We’ll hear about your company, give feedback and recommend the best pitch strategy for the 60-second rapid-fire competition. Think of us as Adam Levine on The Voice.

Pitches will be rated by 3-5 judges, including TechCrunch writers and local VCs. First Place will receive a table in Startup Alley at an upcoming TechCrunch Disrupt. title: ANTHOLOGY FILM ARCHIVES BENEFIT
description:
Jonas Mekas and Co-Chairs Maja Hoffmann and Stanley Buchthal

Present 

The Anthology Film Archives Benefit and Auction

Musical Performance by Patti Smith 


On March 2, Anthology Film Archives, one of the world’s largest and most important repositories of avant-garde film and a New York cultural and architectural landmark, will hold an unparalleled art auction. 

This special evening will raise funds to build the much-awaited Heaven and Earth Library and Café.


THE COMPLETION PROJECT
	

The initial design of Anthology Film Archives included a Library and a Café that have yet to be completed. The Heaven and Earth Café will serve Anthology’s audiences and the neighborhood with proceeds going toward Anthology’s operating costs. The Library and Gallery will enable Anthology to unpack and make available to scholars and students all the unique books, documents, art collections (Harry Smith, Paul Sharits, Jim Davis, Joseph Cornell, Jerome Hill, Kenneth Anger, and many many others). And the elevator will finally enable film lovers with disabilities to access the upper floor theater.

title: TENTH AVENUE NORTH Assumption beONE Concert Series
description:
If every album serves as a single snapshot of an artist’s current
season, then Tenth Avenue North’s new album,

Group), is a Polaroid coming to life in full color. Brilliant hues of
exuberance, confidence and unwavering hope saturate the band’s follow-up to

Brendon Shirley (keys, vocals), Ruben Juarez (bass, vocals) and Jason Jamison
(drums) basking in the pure joy discovered only in following Christ.

Tenth Avenue North has long been known for the depth and vulnerability of their songwriting since they released their acclaimed national debut, Over and Underneath, in 2008. Quickly winning fans’ allegiance with radio staples like “Love Is Here,” “Hold My Heart” and “By Your Side” (GMA’s 2010 Song of the Year), the band was named the Gospel Music Association’s New Artist of the Year in 2009. The group gained further momentum with three additional full-length records that spawned hits like “You Are More,” “Losing,” “Worn” and “No Man Is an Island,” among others, and has sold in excess of one million albums to date.

title: Chicken Wing Workshop with Tablespoon Cooking Co.
description:
Want to learn how to make restaurant-quality chicken wings at home? Come join us for our chicken wing workshop. We’ll cover everything you need to know in order to make the best wings in your own kitchen. 

We’ll talk about purchasing good quality chicken, brining and curing, frying vs. baking, and how to create signature sauces to go with your wings. Of course, we’ll need some blue cheese and ranch for dipping.


Menu


	Fried Buffalo Wings
	Extra Crispy Oven Baked Wings
	2 Signature Sauces 
	Homemade Ranch Dressing
	Homemade Blue Cheese Dressing

You’ll get hands-on experience making two different types of chicken wings. The atmosphere will be fun and convivial and we’ll have beer and wine. We’ll eat and drink throughout class. This makes for a great date night, night out with friends or evening with your parents/adult children!


Important Event Details

CLASS FORMAT: This is a semi hands-on class. We will all work together to cook the recipes. Everyone will get their hands dirty and be involved in each recipe. This class is limited to 12 students.

SKILL LEVEL: All skill levels are welcome! From beginners to expert chefs, this class is for everyone.

FOOD: There will be a welcome snack for when you arrive and then we will eat throughout class. You’ll get to taste everything we are preparing.

ALLERGIES AND DIETARY RESTRICTIONS: Please let me know of any allergies or dietary restrictions IN ADVANCE and we can talk about accommodations.

DRINKS: I will provide local craft beer, wine water. You’re welcome to bring non-alcoholic beverages to class with you.

ADDRESS: Findlay Kitchen is located at 1719 Elm St. Cincinnati, OH 45202

PARKING: There is often street parking available or you can park in one of the Findlay Market lots. Parking info can be found on the Findlay Market website.

ARRIVAL: The classroom kitchen is all windows and located directly inside the main Findlay Kitchen entrance. You’ll see us when you walk up. The doors will be locked so just knock/buzz and we’ll let you in. We will be watching for arrivals so it shouldn’t be an issue. Please try to arrive around 5:45 pm so we can get started on time.

ATTIRE: Please wear closed toed, non-slip shoes. Please keep your hair pulled back or wear a hat. Otherwise, wear comfortable clothes that could potentially get a little dirty. I will provide aprons. Also, feel free to bring clothes if you need to change after work. There is a nice, clean bathroom where you can change.

WHAT TO BRING: Nothing!

Questions? Email jordan@tablespoooncookingco.com

title: TWIN PEAKS: FIRE WALK WITH ME presented with Debrodniks Donuts
description:
To celebrate the return of TWIN PEAKS this Spring, join us for a special screening of David Lynch's dark, demented and exhilarating FIRE WALK WITH ME. Your ticket includes a damn fine LEFT FIELD BREWERY coffee porter (or coffee with Baileys)* and a delicious locally-crafted donut courtesy of our friends at DEBRODNIKS DONUTS!

Calling all wannabe Agent Coopers and Log Ladies, dress up as your favourite TWIN PEAKS character for a chance to win some very cool prizes, including the grand prize of a Golden Apollo Membership - free movies for a year!

Our Apollo's feast food menu will be available for the evening, and all entrees will include a special side of creamed corn! So grab a friend and come to the Black Lodge - sorry Apollo - for dinner and a movie.

7-8pm: BLACK LODGE HOUR Come early and mingle with fellow TWIN PEAKS fans. Have a drink, order some food, and be sure not miss the Costume Contest! 

8pm: MOVIE STARTS

It begins with an axe crashing into a TV set: sparks fly, a scream is heard, and the symbolism is brutally obvious - forget everything you thought you knew about the quirky, wacky, cosy world of TWIN PEAKS, cos Daddy's home and he's pissed off. Like many of the show's hardcore fans, David Lynch was disillusioned with what TWIN PEAKS had become: from a groundbreaking, excoriating peek into America's small-town underbelly to a cute parade of oddball soap-operatics in under two years. The big screen version gave him licence to bring it all back to basics, and he grabbed it with both hands: even in Lynch-land, with all its ear-severing, head-exploding, exploitation and rough sex, there's nothing so dark and demented as FIRE WALK WITH ME, now regarded as one of his best films -- a masterpiece alongside BLUE VELVET and MULHOLLAND DRIVE. The critics sneered, the fans balked and the public stayed away in droves. It's their loss: this was a beautiful new kind of madness, terrifying, exhausting and exhilarating in equal measure. BE WARNED THOUGH: If you do plan on watching the series, see it first; this film contains one helluva of a spoiler.

*Non-alcoholic options available

title: Highly Fabulous 2017 (London) - STEP UP AND STEP OUT
description:
This Women's Conference  is where highly fabulous women come to celebrate each other's triumphs and successes.  To learn from each other's journey and be empowered.  The place where women connect on a highly fabulous level. When it comes to surroundings where women shift into a space that completely enables  their dreams, this is it.

Speakers:

DeVon Franklin and Meagan Good, Hollywood Power Couple, authors of The Wait. They will speak on relationships and how the person you marry can alter the direction of your life.

Tera Carissa-Hodges from Atlanta, GA, one of the most influential voices today among women leaders.  Tera  will speak on Standing in your Purpose. If you're looking for someone who speaks powerful truth you can take to the bank, Tera is the one.

Felicia Philips, the 6 figure Mastermind Business Woman, listed in Who's Who in Atlanta, will give the real inside track on how you can make it in business whether there is a recession going on or not, just as she has done  for more than 20 years. Founder of the Pink Preneur Network, Felicia is  known as the Pink Mogul because she shows women not only how to build businesses but how to create empires.

Diane Robertson Martin  Cbe, based right here in the UK, a powerful advocate for women and a political activist. Diane was tricked into prostitution and sex trafficked to a foreign country. Not only has she lived to tell the tale but she is now working with several agencies to help provide an exit strategy to those still caught up in that industry. The Queen awarded her the Cbe in 2013 for her work in helping vulnerable women.

Tola Onigbanjo - the curator of the award body Women 4 Africa which has earned the title of the largest gathering of African women in Europe and caught the attention of Bloomberg who reached out for an interview.  Tola will speak to us about having the confidence to raise your head above the parapet and to do what other people tell you is quite impossible.

Dorothelia Barnett - CEO and Editor in Chief of an awarded Women's magazine.  She is also a powerful business Woman and keynote speaker. She shares her personal story and gives lessons on the way life can interupt your plans and how love can sometimes be the dangerous kind of love when you find yourself literally running for your life.

Susanne Kirlew - TV Chef and Pride Magazine Food columnist, Susanne takes us through her journey into media as a woman and a woman of colour. She says sometimes the support from those in her own circle was less than forthcoming. Susanne is proof you can make it in media despite the saboteurs. She has a vegan cooking show in the USA entitled Kirly-Sue's Kitchen, on 3ABN TV which has been running for 4 years.

Dr Ryeal Simms from Hollywood Calif  - the love doctor who breaks down the reasons why we do what we do and speaks on how we can prepare for love so we do not need to repair.  Former resident counsellor to the Tavis Smiley Institute, he is a certified and licensed counselor with the Coaching Institute and the Prepare/Enrich Program.

Facilitators

Andrea Photiou - National recognition for enterprise, Internet radio specialist  and the Online Editor for the Voice Newspaper.

Toni Kelly - TV and awarded Radio Presenter and public speaker.

description:

How the Auction Works:

Each guest will receive a paddle at the door which they use to bid. Guests bid on quality vendor items with one to four quarters, depending on the retail value. Once all bids are placed, a randomly chosen number is called. If that person with that number placed a bid, he or she wins that item. Numbers will continued to be drawn until there is a winner. Bids are collected before each drawing and go to the respective vendor. Proceeds from ticket sales and donations will be donated to Betty Griffin. We are going to have a blast! Betty Griffin House 

To offer protection and quality services for victims of Domestic Violence and their minor children and/or victims of Sexual Assault and their families of St. Johns County, FL, through operation of a shelter offering assistance, counseling, and transitional support.

To educate the community about services provided and raise awareness of the problems of Domestic Violence and Sexual Assault in order to break cycles of abuse.

title: Cheerful Giving Today!
description:
Since 2009, The Women’s Challenge, Inc. (“TWC”) has made a concerted effort to support women. With this goal close to our hearts, we are acutely aware that they may need more than moral support and a listening ear. With each fundraiser, we endeavor to earmark funds to support, encourage and uplift our women, but we can do more, with your help.

Going beyond a support network.

TWC endeavors to help women in the following ways:


	Down payments and/or closing cost assistance for a first-time, female homebuyer
	Funds for our honorees to assist other women who are going through similar medical and/or emotional experiences 
	Entertainment events to help women unwind with music, fun and friends to get a short break from the pressures of being everything to everyone 

We need your help.

We cannot do this alone and need partners to help us provide these grants. Your tax-deductible donation can go a long way and make a major difference.

We host 5-6 annual fundraisers to cover operating expenses for the organization, and provide financial resources for women we honor for their strength, courage and contribution to their communities.

It could be any one of us. 

Our commitment to continue helping these women is born out of the belief that it could be our mother, sister, daughter or friend struggling.  We take pride in empowering every woman we encounter and helping those we can directly impact with our organization.

Your tax-deductible donation of $100 or more would help the women we serve help others; and, pay it forward!

Many of the women directly impacted by TWC are professionals with businesses of their own. We stand with them as they build their businesses, fulfill their dreams of home ownership and move towards a more prosperous and fulfilling life.

title: International Style Institute: Styling Course
description:
Co-founded by Simply Stylist's, Sarah Boyd, and renowned celebrity stylist, Anita Patrickson, the International Style Institute launched in March 2015 with a mission to provide aspiring stylists with the education and resources they need to start a successful styling career whether it be celeb, editorial or personal.

The 3-day intensive course is taught by Anita Patrickson, who has worked with celebrities like Emma Watson, Julianne Hough and Emmy Rossum and has styled covers of ELLE, InStyle, Marie Claire and more with industry expert guest speakers. The course has a 50 attendee maximum to ensure everyone receives individualized attention and mentorship, and 1 promising attendee will be selected to receive a paid day assisting Anita!
Attendees will walk away with a syllabus containing all information necessary on how to be a successful stylist, a list of industry contacts, a Stylist Starter Kit, 1 professional photo styled by the attendee during a live photoshoot and a gift bag with a value up to $500. All graduates will also receive a certificate of completion and be included in our alumni network that includes assistant jobs and internships.
______________________________________

DAY 1: Styling 101

Anita will share her path to becoming a top stylist and show you everything you need to know about styling fundamentals: prepping for a photoshoot, how to build and use your stylist kit, branding, invoicing and billing and more. Anita will be host industry leaders as guest speakers to elaborate on all facets of the industry from fashion publicists, to stylist agents, to top fashion brand representatives. On occasion, we even get a surprise appearance from one of Anita's clients like Chrissy Teigen or a video chat from Julianne Hough!

DAY 2: Celebrity Styling

Anita will walk you through the dos and don'ts of celebrity styling such as how to select designers to borrow from and what to ask your client before taking on a project. You will be partnered up with another attendee and tasked with styling each other. The day will wrap with Project Runway-style feedback from Anita as she walks through each partnership's looks.

DAY 3: Editorial

On the final day of the International Style Institute you will learn everything you need to know about styling an editorial shoot from writing a request letter, to creating mood boards, to working with your photographer. You will have the opportunity to style a professional model and work with a professional photographer, alongside Anita and her team to mentor and assist, and leave with a glossy, retouched image to launch your portfolio!

The course concludes with a commencement hour where each attendee receives their certificate of completion and a celebratory cocktail party to network and bond with their classmates!

Each chef will serve one pork option and one vegetarian option. Stay tuned for official menus & pairings!

Also featuring live and local music from Erin and the Wildfire and Jon Spear Band, with special performances from the Albemarle Pipes & Drums and Irish Dance Club of UVA. title: KidProv at the Push Comedy Theater
description:
Don't miss out on the fun!!! Sign up your kids, grand kids, nieces, nephews, even the stinky neighbor kid from down the street for KidProv at the Push Comedy Theater.

This class is open to children ages 7 to 12. Students will explore the key elements of both long and short form improvisation. The children will play numerous improv games which will serve to develop and enhance their public-speaking, social and team-building skills.

This class will be conducted in a non-judgmental environment where the students will build confidence, make friends and most importantly ... have fun

The session concludes with the students performing in a graduation show on the Push Comedy Theater Stage.

This class will be held from 10:00am-12:00pm on Saturday mornings From January 14th through February 18th.

This is class is $150 for new students and $140 for returning students.

New students also receive a free tshirt.

---

Mary and Jim Veverka collectively have over eight years experience studying and performing improv. Mary, a former children's librarian, has been a professional storyteller for 20+ years. During that time, Jim assisted Mary by playing a variety of characters at holiday events. Prior to moving to the Hampton Roads area, Mary was selected as an adjudicated artist by the Indiana Arts Commission. Mary has also taught storytelling to adults and children of all ages at schools, libraries and other venues.

--

The Push Comedy Theater is a 99 seat venue in the heart of Norfolk's brand new Arts District. Founded by local comedy group The Pushers, the Push Comedy Theater is dedicated to bringing you live comedy from the best local and national acts.

The Push Comedy Theater hosts live sketch, improv and stand-up comedy on Friday and Saturday nights. During the week classes are offered in stand-up, sketch and improv comedy as well as acting and film production.

Whether you're a die-hard comedy lover or a casual fan... a seasoned performer or someone who's never stepped foot on stage... the Push Comedy Theater has something for you.

description: ‘Tis true there is taming, but of whom, and by whom? As our participation in the year long celebration of Shakespeare 400, we bring you his most famous and furious battle of the sexes. title: EUFF Classics: The Shop on Main Street
description:
Directed by Ján Kadár, Elmar Klos | Slovakia, 125 min | 1965, Language: Slovak

An inept Slovak peasant is torn between greed and guilt when the Nazi-backed bosses of his town appoint him “Aryan controller” of an old Jewish widow’s button shop. Humor and tragedy fuse in this scathing exploration of one cowardly man’s complicity in the horrors of a totalitarian regime. Made near the height of Soviet oppression in Czechoslovakia, The Shop on Main Street features intense editing and camera work which won it the Academy Award™ for Best Foreign Film in 1965.

title: United Palace of Cultural Arts Presents: Ballet Hispánico en Familia
description:
Bring the whole family to a 90-minute, fun-filled journey through Latin American dance and culture featuring Artistic Director Eduardo Vilaro as host, excerpts from Ballet Hispánico’s diverse repertory and a Q&A with the dancers.



March 11, 2017

Doors 1pm, Show 2pm, Q&A 3pm

$15 - $25; Free for children 12 and under



Repertory for Ballet Hispánico en Familia includes:

Línea Recta (2016)

Choreography by Annabelle Lopez Ochoa

From one of today’s most sought-after choreographers comes a powerful and resonant work that explores an intriguing aspect of flamenco dance: the conspicuous absence of physical contact between dancers. While maintaining the integrity and hallmark passion of the genre, Belgo-Colombian Annabelle Lopez Ochoa imagines an original and explosive movement language premised upon the theme of communication between the sexes and performed to an original guitar composition by Eric Vaarzon Morel.



Flabbergast (2001)

Choreography by Gustavo Ramírez Sansano


	
	


	

Latin lounge meets spontaneous combustion in this quirky yet joyful piece set to the music of Juan García Esquivel. Inspired by his experience of coming to America for the first time, choreographer Gustavo Ramírez Sansano exposes with humor our stereotypes and preconceived ideas about new and foreign places. Flabbergast is dedicated to the choreographer's mother, who taught him how to dance the bayón.



Club Havana (2000)

Choreography by Pedro Ruiz


	
	


	

A portrait of the glamorous Havana of the 1950s during the heyday of Cuban music, dance and nightlife. The intoxicating rhythms of the conga, rumba, mambo, and cha cha are brought to life by choreographer Pedro Ruiz, a native of Cuba, in this re-imagined nightclub filled with the exhilarating sounds, colors and ambience of that golden era.



Asuka (2011)

Choreography by Eduardo Vilaro


	
	


	

Asuka is a celebration of the music of Celia Cruz through the lens of the Latino experience. Cruz, renowned as the "Queen of Salsa," captured the heart of Latinos the world over and became a symbol of perseverance for many. Through rich imagery and humor, Eduardo Vilaro explores the struggles of departure from one’s homeland and the exuberance of success experienced by a community.



About Ballet Hispánico:
America’s premier Latino dance organization for more than 45 years, Ballet Hispánico brings communities together to celebrate and explore Latino cultures and the shared human experience through dance. Founded by National Medal of Arts recipient Tina Ramirez, Ballet Hispánico has been led since 2009 by Artistic Director & CEO Eduardo Vilaro, who has infused the organization’s legacy with a bold and eclectic brand of contemporary dance that reflects America’s changing cultural landscape. Through performances of its internationally-acclaimed Company, innovative dance training programs, and community education activities that inspire individuals of all ages and backgrounds, Ballet Hispánico brings the joy of dance and Hispanic culture to the world.

title: EUFF Classics: Good Bye Lenin!
description:
Directed by Wolfgang Becker | Germany, 121 min, Language: German

October 1989. In East Berlin, Alex’ mother, a staunch socialist, falls into a coma only to wake up after the fall of the Berlin Wall. Will her weak heart withstand the triumph of capitalism in her beloved country? To save his mother, Alex transforms the family apartment into an island of the past, a kind of socialist museum where his mother is lovingly duped into believing that nothing has changed. What begins as a little white lie gets out of hand as mum wants to watch TV and even leaves her bed one day...

In a wonderful, touching and comic manner, the multi-award-winning Good Bye Lenin! tells the story of how a loving son tries to move mountains to restore his mother to health - and keep her in the belief that Lenin really did win after all.

title: Michael Schatte with Shawn Dore in the Blues in Small Spaces Series
description:
Michael:

It is no exaggeration to say that Michael Schatte (pronounced SHAW-tee) has emerged as one of the most compelling guitarists and singer/songwriters on the North American roots music scene. Since early 2015, when he was a top-eight finalist at the Memphis International Blues Challenge and performed at Tennessee’s historic Orpheum Theatre, Schatte has appeared on some of the continent’s best festival and theatre stages, winning new fans and a reputation for world-class musicianship by way of more than 200 concerts in Canada and the United States. Though Schatte loves the blues (and evidently does it well), it’s just one ingredient in what he calls Eclectic Electric Roots Music, a brew of original rock, blues, celtic, bluegrass, country and rockabilly he’s been writing, recording, and performing throughout his career.

This unique blend of genres is delivered with stunning impact on his latest studio album, Turn Back the Vikings. Recorded in his home base of Toronto and mixed in Austin, Texas by Simon Tassano (the live and studio engineer of choice for folk-rock legend Richard Thompson, whose Sam Jones is the sole cover song on Vikings), the new album is Michael’s finest work to date, prompting Britain’s Blues Matters! magazine to call him “one of the best undiscovered songwriters of our times.” Intelligent lyrics, hook-filled arrangements, and Schatte’s rich singing voice certainly have a way of capturing attention, but it’s his work on a certain six-string plank of wood that ties it all together musically.

A respected and fiery guitarist, Schatte has developed the habit of leaving audience jaws agape. He’s been compared to world-class players decades his senior, and counts Peter Green, Danny Gatton, Albert Lee, Mark Knopfler and of course the aforementioned Richard Thompson as major influences on both his electric and acoustic fingerstyle playing. Reviewing a recent concert at Aeolian Hall in London, The Beat Magazine described Schatte as “one of Canada’s best-kept secrets and certainly one of its most skilled rock performers,” citing his “masterful manipulation of the guitar” and a vocal style “as polished as his picking.”



Shawn:

Jaw dropping guitar and vocals with grooves that live forever! Shawn "Deepwater" Dore is a solo artist that performs a folk blues / country blues type mix of covers (Robert Johnson, Booker White, Muddy Waters, etc.) as well as a great selection of originals from his solo album "Less is More", and from the "Watch My Back" album recorded with the Shawn Dore Band. Also having the ability to involve and connect with the audience, you will surely leave a Deepwater Dore show with a lasting impression.

*Shawn was a competitor representing the Loyal Blues Fellowship at the 2014 International Blues Challenge in Memphis TN, and was one of the acts selected for a showcase performance on Beale Street in Memphis.

“Shawn Dore is a musician, who’s passion shows through, as he plays and sings with reckless abandon every time he hit’s the stage.”-Erin McCallum, musician, winner of the 2012 International Songwriting Competition, 2 time Canadian Maple Blues Award nominee, 2 time Ontario Independent Music Award nominee.

description:

Earlybird Tickets Avail $10-19 / $20 DOS



Horse Meat Disco (London)
The UK’s finest disco operators, Horse Meat Disco, return with another killer album of tried and tested underground disco, Italo and rarities that have been rocking crowds from their base in Vauxhall, London, to dancefloors worldwide during 2009-10.Since their acclaimed debut compilation on Strut in 2009, residents James Hillard, Jim Stanton, Severino and Luke Howard (aka Filthy Luka) have continued to lead the way with their packed residencies at The Eagle, London, Lux in Lisbon, Tape in Berlin and Cihan in Istanbul. During 2010, as well as revisiting UK festivals like Glastonbury, Lovebox and T In The Park, they will be spreading the disco love to some of the world’s leading festivals also so watch this space!Horse Meat Disco Volume 2 brings together another essential selection of New York classics alongside a host of lesser known discoveries for all fans of underground disco. Anthems include Zanzibar favourite ‘You Can Get Over’ by Stephanie Mills, Italo staple ‘Walkman’ by Kasso and Rinder & Lewis’ ‘Afrodesia’ under their El Coco pseudonym. Rarities include ‘I’m Not In Love (Girl You’re In Love)’ by Freda Payne’s sister Scherrie, ‘Cherchez Pas’ by Swedish model-turned-singer Madleen Kane and Italo oddity ‘’Touch Me Now’ by Bravo.Horse Meat Disco is dedicated to the industry of human happiness and it pumps it out every Sunday at THE EAGLE LONDON (formerly South Central). Its the queer party for everyone; Homos and Heteros, club kids, bears, fashionistas, naturists, guerilla drag queens and ladies who munch. Musically its a disco behemoth of classics, italo disco, oddities, punk funk in the friendliest venue south of the river. Plus weekly buffet, happy hour, decorations, and spontaneous acts of exhibitionism.

title: TEDxGrandForks: Breaking Bread
description:
The theme of TEDxGrandForks 2017, Breaking Bread, is the idea of building community and opening the table to more, not fewer, people. When you engage in the physical act of sitting down at a table, joining together with someone, you meet at a neutral point where you are open to listening, learning, and engaging. Breaking Bread speaks to the idea behind the physicality of eating together. Opening your mind to ideas you may disagree with, ideas you may not have considered, ideas you passionately agree with, ideas that make you happy, angry, and sad; all of these thoughts and emotions are accepted at the table. It's a place where you can engage, listen, and contemplate the big things, taking time to learn and grow from one another. Welcome to Breaking Bread - take a bite, chew it, and join us in engaging our ideas and our community.

TEDxGrandForks is proud to showcase our inspiring, local presenters on multiple platforms to reach a diverse and global audience, including live streaming our annual conference and uploading professionally produced videos for international access. With talks from local and national minds, TEDxGrandForks 2017 will bring together both local and national thought leaders to educate our community, ignite our curiosity, activate our sense of possibility, and, ultimately, instill a desire for meaningful change.
